    -- Topic 59: Data Lake Architecture (5 questions)
    (291, 'What is a data lake? How does it differ from a data warehouse? When would you use each?',
     'Data lake: centralized repository storing all data in raw format (structured, semi-structured, unstructured), schema-on-read, scalable storage. Example: S3 buckets with logs, JSON, Parquet, images, videos. Data warehouse: structured repository for analytics, processed data, schema-on-write, optimized for queries. Example: Snowflake with cleaned tables, star schema. Key differences: Schema - lake: schemaon-read (apply schema when reading), warehouse: schema-on-write (enforce schema when loading). Data types - lake: any format (images, logs, JSON), warehouse: structured tables. Processing - lake: raw data, transform later, warehouse: curated data, transformed before load. Users - lake: data scientists (explore, ML), data engineers (processing), warehouse: analysts (BI, reporting). Cost - lake: cheap storage (S3 pennies/GB), warehouse: more expensive (compute + storage). Query - lake: slower (raw data, no optimization), warehouse: faster (indexed, columnar). Use data lake for: (1) Storing all data before knowing use case, (2) Machine learning (need raw features), (3) Exploration, (4) Long-term archival (cheap), (5) Unstructured data (logs, images). Use warehouse for: (1) BI and reporting, (2) Known queries, (3) Business users need fast access, (4) Governed, curated data. Modern: data lakehouse combines both (Databricks Delta Lake, Apache Iceberg), ACID transactions on lake, query performance like warehouse, single platform.',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (292, 'Explain the concept of a lakehouse. What problems does it solve? Compare Delta Lake, Apache Iceberg, and Apache Hudi.',
     'Lakehouse: unified platform combining data lake (cheap storage, all data types) and data warehouse (ACID, performance), eliminate two-tier architecture. Problems solved: (1) Data duplication - traditional: raw in lake, curated in warehouse (duplicate). Lakehouse: single copy. (2) Consistency - keeping lake and warehouse in sync complex. Lakehouse: ACID transactions ensure consistency. (3) Governance - hard to govern raw lake. Lakehouse: schema enforcement, access control. (4) Performance - querying raw lake slow. Lakehouse: optimizations (indexing, caching, columnar format). Delta Lake (Databricks): open-source storage layer, ACID transactions on S3/cloud storage, time travel (query historical versions), schema enforcement, Delta tables. Pros: mature, Spark integration, excellent documentation, Unity Catalog integration. Cons: Spark-centric, less ecosystem beyond Databricks. Apache Iceberg (Netflix): table format, SQL engines can query (Spark,Flink, Presto, Trino), hidden partitioning (query without knowing partitions), schema evolution, time travel, ACID. Pros: engine-agnostic (works with many tools), strong community, excellent for large data. Cons: newer, more complex. Apache Hudi (Uber): similar to Delta/Iceberg, optimized for upserts, incremental processing, record-level updates. Pros: great for CDC, incremental ETL, streaming ingestion. Cons: complexity, Spark-heavy. Comparison: Adoption - Delta (broad via Databricks), Iceberg (growing fast), Hudi (niche). Engines - Iceberg (most agnostic), Delta (Spark mostly), Hudi (Spark). Use cases - Delta: general lakehouse, Iceberg: multi-engine environments, Hudi: CDC-heavy. Trend: Iceberg momentum growing (chosen by Snowflake, Dremio), Delta strong in Databricks ecosystem, all three viable depending on stack. Recommendation: Databricks users → Delta Lake, multi-engine/open → Iceberg, heavy CDC/streaming → Hudi.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),


    (293, 'What is the medallion architecture (Bronze, Silver, Gold)? How do you implement it in a data lake?',
     'Medallion architecture: multi-layer data organization pattern in lakehouse, progressive refinement from raw to curated. Databricks pattern, widely adopted. Layers: Bronze (Raw): exact copy of source data, no transformation, all history preserved, append-only. Example: JSON logs from Kafka, CSV files from SFTP, database dumps. Purpose: data durability, reprocessability, audit trail. Format: original or basic (Parquet for efficiency). Silver (Cleaned/Conformed): validated, cleaned, deduplicated, conformed data, business logic applied, enterprise view. Example: parsed JSON to structured tables, null handling, type conversions, deduplicated records. Purpose: standardized data for analysis. Format: Delta/Iceberg tables. Gold (Curated/Aggregated): business-level aggregates, feature tables for ML, optimized for consumption, star/snowflake schemas. Example: daily_sales summary, customer_360 view, ML features. Purpose: serve analytics, BI, ML. Format: dimension/fact tables, feature store. Data flow: Source → Bronze (EL, just load) → Silver (T, cleaning and conformation) → Gold (T, aggregation and optimization). Implementation: Spark jobs read Bronze → write Silver, Silver → Gold, orchestrated by Airflow/Databricks Workflows. Schema evolution: Bronze schema-on-read (flexible), Silver enforced schema, Gold business schema. Benefits: (1) Separation of concerns (raw vs cleaned vs aggregated), (2) Reprocessability (can rebuild Silver/Gold from Bronze), (3) Incremental processing (each layer independently), (4) Quality gates (validate at Silver, aggregate at Gold), (5) Multi-persona (engineers work Bronze/Silver, analysts Gold). Variations: add Platinum (highly aggregated) or reduce to two layers. Tools: Databricks Delta Live Tables automates medallion pipeline, dbt for transformations across layers.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (294, 'How do you implement data cataloging and metadata management in a data lake?',
     'Data catalog: centralized metadata repository, describes datasets (schema, location, lineage, owners), enables discovery and governance. Problem solved: data lake becomes "data swamp" without catalog (can''t find data, don''t know what exists, no ownership). Components: (1) Technical metadata - schema (columns, types), storage location (S3 path), format (Parquet, JSON), partitioning, size, row count, creation/update timestamps. (2) Business metadata - human-readable descriptions, business glossary terms, data quality metrics, usage stats, owners/stewards. (3) Operational metadata - access logs, query performance, lineage (upstream sources, downstream consumers), transformations. (4) Social metadata - user comments, ratings, tags, popularity. Features: (1) Search - full-text search across metadata, find datasets by name/description/column. (2) Data lineage - visual graph showing data flow. (3) Schema evolution tracking - history of schema changes. (4) Access management - permissions, PII tagging. (5) Quality metrics - profiling stats, test results. Implementation: Manual - developers manually document tables (error-prone, outdated). Automated - crawlers scan data lake, infer schema, extract metadata. Example: AWS Glue Crawler scans S3, creates table definitions in Glue Data Catalog. Hybrid - automated technical metadata + manual business annotations. Tools: Open-source: Apache Atlas (Hadoop ecosystem), Amundsen (Lyft), DataHub (LinkedIn), OpenMetadata. Cloud: AWS Glue Catalog, Azure Purview, GCP Data Catalog. Commercial: Alation, Collibra, Atlan. Integration: Spark/Presto query catalog for schema, BI tools (Tableau, Looker) integrate for discovery, data quality tools publish results to catalog. Governance: Catalog enforces policy (PII tagged datasets require approval for access), compliance reports from catalog, data steward workflows. Best practices: tag PII/sensitive data (GDPR compliance), assign ownership (accountability), keep business descriptions updated (valuable for discoveryonly if accurate), integrate catalog into workflow (not separate system), automate metadata extraction (manual doesn''t scale).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (295, 'Your data lake has grown to 500TB across 100K datasets in S3, but teams are struggling to find relevant data, data quality issues are common, and there''s no clear ownership. Additionally, compliance requires cataloging PII within 30 days but you have no visibility into what data contains PII. Design a governance and cataloging strategy. How do you implement discovery, ensure data quality, establish ownership, and automate PII detection?',
     'Multi-dimensional governance challenge: discovery (find data), quality (trust data), ownership (who responsible), compliance (PII inventory). Diagnosis current state: 100K datasets chaotic (unnamed, undocumented), no schema registry (don''t know structure without querying), PII scattered (untagged, ungoverned), quality variable (some reliable, some garbage), no accountability (who to ask about dataset?). Strategic implementation plan: Phase 1 - Foundational Catalog (Weeks 1-2): (1) Choose catalog platform - AWS Glue Catalog (if AWS-centric, integrated), or Atlan/DataHub (richer features, multi-cloud). Deploy. (2) Automated discovery - run crawlers across entire S3 (AWS Glue Crawlers or custom Spark jobs), extract: datasets locations, infer schemas (Parquet has schema, JSON sample), file formats, partition structures, sizes. Result: technical metadata for 100K datasets in catalog. (3) Quick wins - searchable catalog operational, teams can discover what datasets exist (basic search), already huge improvement from nothing. Phase 2 - PII Detection and Compliance (Weeks 2-4, PRIORITY): Compliance deadline critical. (1) Automated PII scanning - use AWS Macie (scans S3, detects PII patterns like SSN, credit cards, emails) OR custom Spark jobs with regex/ML (scan column names and sample data, flag: name-like, address-like, phone-like patterns). (2) PII tagging in catalog - detected PII → tag datasets/columns in catalog with "PII:SSN", "PII:email", etc. (3) PII inventory report - generate report from catalog tags (which datasets have what PII), submit for compliance. (4) Access controls - restrict PII datasets (require approval workflow), audit access (who queried PII data). Result: compliance deadline met, PII visibility achieved, governance foundation. Phase 3 - Ownership and Accountability (Weeks 3-5): (1) Ownership assignment - identify dataset creators (S3 object metadata, IAM logs for who wrote), contact individuals/teams, assign explicit owners in catalog. (2) Ownership policy - new datasets require owner tag at creation (S3 bucket policy or Lambda trigger), regular ownership reviews (quarterly audit, re-assign orphaned datasets). (3) Stewardship model - data stewards per domain (finance, product, engineering), stewards govern their domain datasets, escalation path for issues. (4) Communication - launch announcement explaining catalog, ownership responsibilities, how to use (documentation, training). Phase 4 - Data Quality Framework (Weeks 4-8): (1) Quality profiling - profile datasets (row counts, null percentages, value distributions) using Great Expectations or custom Spark, publish metrics to catalog (completeness, freshness, volume trends). (2) Quality tagging - categorize datasets by quality tier: Tier 1 (high quality, validated), Tier 2 (medium, basic checks), Tier 3 (raw, use with caution), display in catalog prominently. (3) Automated quality checks - implement pipelines validate critical datasets (Great Expectations suites), scheduled runs, publish results to catalog (dataset X last validated 2024-01-15, 98% pass rate). (4) Quality SLAs - for critical datasets, define quality SLAs (< 1% nulls, freshness < 24hrs), alert owners on violations. Phase 5 - Enhanced Discovery and Usability (Weeks 6-10): (1) Business metadata enrichment - add human-readable descriptions (what is this dataset?), business glossary terms (link "customer" to standard definition), usage examples (sample queries), owners add manually, incentivize (recognition for well-documented data). (2) Automated tagging - ML-basedclassification (analyze column names/values, auto-tag: "financial", "customer", "product"), reduces manual effort. (3) Lineage visualization - implement data lineage tracking (OpenLineage integration, parse Spark/Airflow DAGs), show upstream sources and downstream consumers in catalog, helps understand impact and trust. (4) Search optimizations - faceted search (filter by owner, quality tier, PII status, format), popularity ranking (most queried datasets surface first), recommendations ("users viewing this also viewed..."). Phase 6 - Access Governance and Compliance Automation (Weeks 8-12): (1) Access request workflow - users request access to PII datasets via catalog, approval workflow (route to owner/steward), automated provisioning (IAM role granted). (2) Usage tracking - log who queries what datasets, publish usage stats to catalog (helps identify valuable vs unused data). (3) Retention policies - define data retention (PII deleted after N years, raw logs after 90 days), automated cleanup (S3 lifecycle policies), documented in catalog. (4) Compliance reporting - automated reports (all PII datasets + access logs + retention compliance), ready for audits. Technical implementation details: Catalog infrastructure: AWS Glue + Atlan hybrid (Glue for technical metadata, Atlan for business/collaboration), or DataHub (open-source, full-featured). PII detection: custom Spark job using libraries (Presidio for entity recognition, spaCy for NLP), scan Parquet/Delta tables, sample rows, pattern matching, write tags back to catalog. Data quality: Great Expectations for profiling and validation, integrate with Airflow (scheduled runs), publish results to catalog API. Lineage: OpenLineage integrated into Spark/Airflow, pushes lineage events to catalog, visualize in UI. Ownership enforcement: S3 bucket policy requires "owner" tag on PutObject (Lambda pre-check or deny), + periodic audits finding untagged datasets. Organizational change management: (1) Executive sponsorship - governance initiative approved at exec level, allocate resources. (2) Communication campaign - launch webinar explaining catalog, documentation, office hours for questions. (3) Incentives - recognize teams with best-documented datasets, gamification (leaderboard for most enriched data). (4) Training - onboarding includes catalog usage, data steward training for governance role. (5) Adoption tracking - measure catalog usage (searches, dataset views), track metadata completeness (% datasets with descriptions, owners), iterate based on feedback. Success metrics checkpoint: Discovery - mean time to find relevant dataset < 10 minutes (vs hours), catalog search usage growing, Net Promoter Score from users. Quality - % datasets with quality metrics visible (target 80% within 3 months), critical datasets monitored (SLAs defined and tracked). Ownership - 100% datasets have assigned owners (within 3 months), orphan datasets  < 5%. Compliance - PII inventory complete (met deadline), access to PII datasets governed (approval workflow), audit-ready reports available. Challenges and mitigations: Challenge: Ownership resistance (teams don''t want responsibility). Mitigation: make ownership lightweight (just point of contact, not full-time role), benefits messaging (ownership gives you priority support, visibility). Challenge: Catalog maintenance (becomes stale). Mitigation: automate metadata extraction (crawlers run daily), tie catalog updates to deployment pipelines (can''t deploy without catalog entry). Challenge: Too many datasets (100K overwhelming). Mitigation: prioritize (focus on top 100 most-used datasets first, expand), deprecate unused (sunset datasets not queried in 2 years), consolidate where possible. Challenge: Complex lineage (hard to extract). Mitigation: start simple (document manually for critical paths), expand automation incrementally (instrument new pipelines with OpenLineage, backfill legacy). Long-term sustainability: Catalog as code - metadata in Git (version controlled, reviewed like code), deployed via CI/CD. Shift-left governance - enforce metadata at creation (pipeline templates include catalog registration), not after-the-fact. Continuous improvement - regular governance meetings (review metrics, adjust policies), feedback loop from users. Expected outcomes Year 1: Catalog adoption 80%+, PII compliance maintained, data discovery time reduced 70%, quality issues detected proactively (not by users), strong ownership culture, foundation for advanced governance (data mesh, federated ownership).',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 60: Data Governance (5 questions)
    (296, 'What is data governance? What are the key components of a data governance framework?',
     'Data governance: framework for managing data as asset, ensures quality, security, compliance, usability. Organizational discipline, not just technology. Why needed: regulatory compliance (GDPR, HIPAA), data quality (trusted decisions), risk management (security, privacy), efficiency (reduce duplication, find data faster). Key components: (1) Data stewardship - assign ownership, roles: data owners (business accountable), data stewards (maintain quality), data custodians (technical implementation). (2) Policies and standards - data quality standards, naming conventions, retention policies, access policies, PII handling procedures. (3) Data catalog - metadata repository, discovery, lineage. (4) Data quality - profiling, validation, monitoring, remediation. (5) Access control - who can access what, classification (public, internal, confidential), least privilege. (6) Compliance - regulatory requirements mapped to controls, audit trails, reportingcapabilities. (7) Data lifecycle management - creation, usage, archival, deletion policies. (8) Metrics and KPIs - measure governance effectiveness: data quality scores, policy compliance %, time to access data, incidents. Operating model: (1) Governance council - cross-functional leadership, sets policies, resolves conflicts. (2) Working groups - domain-specific (finance data, customer data), implement policies. (3) Data stewards - day-to-day execution, enforce standards. Maturity model: Level 1 (Ad-hoc): no formal governance. Level 2 (Developing): policies exist, inconsistent enforcement. Level 3 (Defined): formalized processes, documented, trained. Level 4 (Managed): metrics tracked, continuous improvement. Level 5 (Optimized): governance embedded in culture, proactive. Tools: catalogs (Alation, Collibra), quality (Great Expectations, Monte Carlo), access (cloud IAM, Privacera), workflow (Jira, custom). Challenges: cultural, not just technical (people resist governance overhead), balance control vs agility (too strict = slow innovation), sustaining momentum (starts strong, fades).',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (297, 'Explain the concept of data mesh. How does it differ from centralized data platforms?',
     'Data mesh: decentralized data architecture, domain teams own their data as products, federated governance, self-serve platform. Zhamak Dehghani (Thoughtworks) 2019. Principles: (1) Domain-oriented ownership - data owned by domain teams (not central data team), teams accountable for data quality, APIs, usability. Example: checkout team owns order data, marketing team owns campaign data. (2) Data as a product - treat data like product, has consumers (other teams), SLAs, documentation, versioning, discoverability. (3) Self-serve data platform - infrastructure platform teams can use (deploy pipelines, store data, access controls), low friction. (4) Federated computational governance - global standards (security, compliance) centrally defined, execution decentralized, automated policy enforcement. Centralized platform (traditional): central data team owns warehouse/lake, ingests from sources, serves to consumers, bottleneck (all requests through central team), scaling issues (one team can''t handle all domains). Data mesh: domains self-sufficient, publish data products, consume others products, scales organizationally (parallel ownership). Analogy: monolith (centralized) vs microservices (mesh). Comparison: Ownership - central: data team, mesh: domain teams. Scalability - central: bottleneck, mesh: parallel. Complexity - central: simpler (one team, one platform), mesh: complex (coordination). Governance - central: uniform, mesh: federated. Use central when: small organization, simple data landscape, strong central team. Use mesh when: large organization (100s engineers), many domains, scaling issues with central model. Challenges of mesh: coordination across domains, data discoverability (many data products), inconsistent quality (each team different standards), tooling (need self-serve platform). Solutions: strong federated governance (automated checks), excellent data catalog (discovery), platform team builds paved road (easy for domains to comply). Tools: domain data products on Databricks/Snowflake, catalog for discovery (DataHub, Atlan), policy enforcement (Open Policy Agent).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (298, 'What is GDPR? How does it impact data engineering practices? Discuss right to erasure and data portability.',
     'GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation): EU privacy law, effective 2018, protects personal data of EU citizens, applies globally if processing EU citizen data. Fines up to €20M or 4% revenue. Key concepts: Personal data - any info relating to identified/identifiable person (name, email, IP, cookie ID). Processing - any operation on personal data. Data controller - decides why/how to process. Data processor - processes on behalf of controller. Principles: lawfulness, fairness, transparency, purpose limitation, data minimization, accuracy, storage limitation, integrity/confidentiality, accountability. Individual rights: (1) Right to access - individual can request copy of their data. Engineering: need system to extract all data for person (across databases, logs, backups). (2) Right to erasure ("right to be forgotten") - delete personal data upon request (with exceptions). Engineering: soft delete (flag as deleted, anonymize) or hard delete (physically remove from databases, backups, logs), cascading deletes (everywhere person exists), challenges: backups (hard to delete from old backups, solution: anonymize before), logs (immutable, solution: don''t log PII or anonymize), data lake (find and delete from Parquet files, complex). (3) Right to data portability - provide data in machine-readable format (JSON, CSV). Engineering: export API, standardized format. (4) Right to rectification - correct inaccurate data. Engineering impact: (1) Data inventory - know what personal data you have, where it is (catalog with PII tagging). (2) Consent management - track consent (what user agreed to), enforce (only use data for consented purpose), withdrawal (delete if consent withdrawn). (3) Anonymization/pseudonymization - techniques to reduce risk: anonymization (irreversible, no longer personal data), pseudonymization (reversible with key, still personal data but lower risk). (4) Data retention - define and enforce retention policies (delete after N months), automated cleanup. (5) Access controls - principle of least privilege, audit who accessed PII. (6) Data processing agreements - contracts with vendors (processors) handling data. (7) Breach notification - detect and report breaches within 72hrs. Implementation: PII tagging in catalog, soft delete architecture (deleted_at timestamp, filter in queries), export APIs for portability, retention policies in data pipelines, encryption at rest/transit, access logging, incident response procedures. Other regulations: CCPA (California), LGPD (Brazil), similar requirements.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (299, 'How do you implement data lineage tracking across a complex data pipeline? What tools and techniques can be used?',
     'Data lineage: complete path data travels, from source → transformations → destination, column-level or table-level. Why critical: impact analysis (change breaks what?), debugging (where did bad data come from?), compliance (prove data handling), trust (understand provenance). Challenges in complex pipelines: multiple tools (Airflow, Spark, dbt, APIs), dynamic SQL (lineage changes based on runtime), black-box systems (vendor tools with no lineage export), scale (thousands of tables, millions of queries). Implementation approaches: (1) Parse query logs - extract SQL from query history (Snowflake, BigQuery query logs), parse SQL to find dependencies (source tables → target table), build lineage graph. Pros: works retroactively. Cons: parsing SQL complex (CTEs, subqueries), may miss non-SQL (API calls). Tools: SQLLineage (Python library parses SQL). (2) Instrument ETL code - add lineage metadata to pipeline code, example: Airflow DAG declares input/output datasets, Spark job annotates sources/sinks. OpenLineage standard: emit lineage events (run started, dataset read, dataset written), collectors aggregate events, visualize in catalog. Integration: Airflow with OpenLineage plugin, Spark with OpenLineage listener. Pros: accurate (declared), real-time. Cons: requires code changes, adoption effort. (3) Metadata extraction from tools - dbt has built-in lineage (manifest.json), Airbyte/Fivetran declare sources/destinations, extract metadata via APIs, combine into unified graph. (4) Column-level lineage - track transformations per column (revenue = SUM(price * quantity)), parse SELECT statements, track column dependencies. Complex (derivations through many transformations), high value (trace specific field). Tools: SQLFlow, Querybook. (5) Manual documentation - for complex logic, document lineage manually, stored in catalog, labor-intensive but captures business logic. Tooling: Open-source: Apache Atlas (Hadoop ecosystem, manual lineage + hooks), Amundsen (table-level lineage), DataHub (OpenLineage integration, rich lineage), OpenMetadata (emerging, comprehensive), Marquez (OpenLineage reference implementation). Commercial: Alation, Collibra, Atlan, Manta (specialized in lineage). Visualization: graph databases (Neo4j) store lineage (nodes = tables/columns, edges = transformations), UI queries graph (show upstream/downstream). Best practices: (1) Start with critical paths - lineage for revenue tables first, expand later. (2) Automate where possible - parsing, tool integrations, reduce manual. (3) Standard conventions - consistent dataset naming, clear transformation docs. (4) Real-time lineage - emit during pipeline execution (not batch), timely. (5) Column-level where it matters - not everything needs column-level, prioritize. Example stack: OpenLineage as standard → Airflow/Spark emit events → Marquez/DataHub collect → visualize in catalog → analysts query "what feeds this dashboard?".',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (300, 'You need to implement GDPR "right to erasure" across your data ecosystem which includes PostgreSQL (user profiles), MongoDB (user activity logs), S3 data lake (event logs in Parquet), Snowflake warehouse (analytics tables), and ElasticSearch (search indexes). A user requests deletion. Walk through the technical implementation. What are the challenges with backups, logs, and analytics data? How do you ensure complete erasure while maintaining referential integrity?',
     'GDPR erasure request scope: must delete all personal data for user across all systems within 30 days (reasonable timeframe), burden of proof on organization (demonstrate complete removal). Systems inventory: PostgreSQL (OLTP, structured, relational), MongoDB (document store, semi-structured), S3 (immutable logs, append-only), Snowflake (warehouse, analytical queries), Elasticsearch (search, inverted index). Each has unique erasure challenges. Technical implementation framework: Phase 1 - User Identification (Day 1): (1) Collect user identifiers - primary: email,user_id. Secondary: session cookies, device IDs, IP addresses (if linked to user). (2) Expand identifiers - query systems to find all related IDs (user has multiple emails? pseudonymous IDs?), build comprehensive list. (3) Log erasure request - legal requirement (who requested, when, completed when), audit trail. Phase 2 - Data Discovery (Days 1-3): (1) User data inventory - query each system for user_id presence: PostgreSQL: SELECT tables WHERE columns match user_id, MongoDB: search collections for user documents, S3: scan partitions likely containing user (if partitioned by date, check user signup date onwards), Snowflake: query information_schema, find tables with user_id column, Elasticsearch: search indexes for user documents. (2) Dependency mapping - referential integrity: orders table references user_id (foreign key), what to do with user''s orders? Options: delete cascading (remove orders too, may violate financial regulations), anonymize user data but keep orders (replace user_id with "DELETED_USER"), soft delete user (mark deleted, keep relational integrity). Decision depends on business/legal requirements. Phase 3 - Erasure Execution (Days 3-7): Execute in order (avoid FK constraint violations): (1) PostgreSQL: BEGIN TRANSACTION; - Option A (hard delete): DELETE FROM orders WHERE user_id = 'X'; DELETE FROM users WHERE user_id = 'X'; - Option B (anonymize): UPDATE users SET name = 'Deleted User', email = NULL, hashed_email = NULL, phone = NULL WHERE user_id = 'X'; UPDATE orders SET user_email = NULL WHERE user_id = 'X'; COMMIT; Anonymization preferred for relational integrity + compliance (data not personal if not identifiable). (2) MongoDB: db.user_activity.deleteMany({ user_id: "X"  }) - OR anonymize fields: db.user_activity.updateMany({ user_id: "X" }, { $unset: { email: "", ip_address: "", device_id: "" } }) MongoDB easier (no FK constraints), can fully delete or anonymize. (3) S3 Data Lake (complex!): Challenge: Parquet files immutable, can''t edit in-place. Solutions: (a) Rewrite files: read Parquet files containing user data (partition pruning helps), filter out user rows, write new files, replace old (S3 update is copy + delete). Expensive for large data! (b) Tombstone markers: write "deleted user" metadata file (user_id X deleted), queries apply filter at read time (Spark: df.filter(user_id != deleted_users)), data physically remains but logically erased. Cheaper, eventual physical deletion via compaction. (c) Partitioning strategy: if partitioned by user_id, delete entire partition (simple!), but rarely partitioned this way. Implementation: Spark job: spark.read.parquet("s3://events/").filter(user_id != "X").write.parquet("s3://events_cleaned/") Replace original, may take hours for large data. (4) Snowflake: DELETE FROM analytics.user_events WHERE user_id = 'X'; UPDATE analytics.aggregated_sales SET customer_email = NULL WHERE user_id = 'X'; Snowflake supports DELETE (updates metadata, physical removal during clustering), OR UPDATE to anonymize. For large tables, DELETE can be slow (mark rows deleted, compaction lazily removes), monitor Time Travel (Snowflake keeps deleted rows for 1-90 days, ensure Time Travel period acceptable or PURGE). (5) Elasticsearch: POST /user_index/_delete_by_query { "query": { "match": { "user_id": "X" } } } Deletes matching documents, reindex if large volume, Elasticsearch async deletes. Phase 4 - Backup Handling (Critical Challenge): Problem: backups contain historical personal data, can''t easily delete from old backups (immutable snapshots). Solutions: (a) Backup retention policy: align backup retention with data retention (if delete user after 2 years inactive, keep backups < 2 years), automatic expiration (older backups deleted, user data naturally purged). (b) Anonymize before backup: backup anonymized data (ETL anonymizes PII before backup), difficult for OLTP (need real data for operations). (c) Exclude from restore: mark user as deleted in live system, if restore from backup, reapply deletions (restore → run deletion scripts again), maintains compliance even if backup had data. (d) Backup encryption + key destruction: encrypt backups per-user keys, delete key = data irrecoverable (extreme, rarely practical). Practical approach: document that backups retained for disaster recovery (legitimate interest), if backup restored, erasure re-executed (user remains deleted). Most GDPR guidance accepts this. Phase 5 - Log Files (Immutable Challenge): Application logs (Access logs, error logs) contain PII (IP, email, request params). Problem: logs append-only, immutable for tamper-proofing, distributed across many files. Solutions: (a) Dont log PII - best practice, log user_id only (not email, IP), prevents issue entirely. (b) Log rotation + retention - short retention (30 days), auto-delete old logs, user data naturally purged by retention. (c) Pseudonymization in logs - hash user_id before logging, can't reverse to identify user, technically compliant (pseudonymous data has lower risk). (d) Queryable logs - logs in Elasticsearch/Splunk, can delete by query (like Elasticsearch above), expensive storage but enables erasure. Recommendation: combine (dont log PII where possible + short retention + queryable for critical systems). Phase 6 - Validation and Audit (Days 7-14): (1) Confirm deletion - re-query all systems (should return zero results for user_id), automated script: check_user_exists(user_id, all_systems), assert all return False. (2) Audit trail - log completion (user X deleted from systems Y, Z on date D, by engineer E), evidence for regulatory inquiry. (3) Notify user - confirmation email (if email not deleted!) or response to request channel, "Your data has been deleted". Challenges and edge cases: Challenge 1: User re-registers with same email - deleted flag prevents? Or allow (fresh start, compliant if previous data truly deleted). Challenge 2: Analytics aggregates - user contributed to aggregate (e.g., "monthly user count"), deleting user changes historical metrics (breaks analytics). Solution: aggregates usually acceptable (user not individually identifiable in count), document rationale. Challenge 3: Financial/legal holds - Cannot delete if legal obligation to retain (tax records 7 years), exception to GDPR right to erasure, document and notify user ("data retained for tax compliance, deleted after retention period"). Challenge 4: Derived data - ML model trained on user data, must delete? GDPR unclear, models typically OK if user not identifiable in model weights, document reasoning. Challenge 5: Third-party vendors - data shared with partners (email provider, analytics vendor), erasure request must extend to them, Data Processing Agreements require vendors comply, notify vendors, track compliance. Automation and tooling: Build erasure pipeline: (1) Intake: erasure request via UI/API → ticket created (Jira, ServiceNow). (2) Orchestration: Airflow DAG triggered, task per system (PostreSQL task, S3 task, etc.), parallel execution where possible (independent systems), serial where dependencies (delete orders before user). (3) Validation: automated checks post-deletion, assert user gone. (4) Audit: log all actions, store in compliance DB. (5) Notification: email user confirmation. Infrastructure: Privacy engineering team builds/maintains erasure service, self-serve for common cases (user does it themselves), manual intervention for complex cases. Preventive measures (reduce future burden): (1) Data minimization - dont collect unnecessary PII, less to delete. (2) Retention policies - auto-delete old data, user data purged automatically after inactivity period (GDPR allows, reduces erasure requests). (3) Anonymization - anonymize for analytics (real user data only in OLTP), analytics warehouse has anonymized IDs (can't tie back to person). (4) Privacy by design - build erasure capability into new systems upfront, easier than retrofitting. Expected timeline: Simple user (only in core systems): 7 days. Complex user (across many systems, large S3 data): 14-30 days. Backup + log purge (natural retention): months (acceptable under GDPR as long as in progress). Success criteria: Zero user PII retrievable across all systems, audit trail complete, user notified, process documented for future requests (next user faster).',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 61: Change Data Capture (CDC) (5 questions)
    (301, 'What is Change Data Capture (CDC)? Why is it useful? Compare log-based CDC vs query-based CDC.',
     'Change Data Capture (CDC): technique to identify and capture changes in source database (inserts, updates, deletes), stream changes to target system in real-time or near-real-time. Use cases: data replication (sync source DB to warehouse), real-time analytics (stream changes to Kafka), event sourcing (audit all changes), cache invalidation (update cache when DB changes). Query-based CDC: poll database for changes using timestamp or version column. Example: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE updated_at > last_poll_time. Pros: simple (just SQL), no special DB config, works with any DB. Cons: polling overhead (repeated queries strain DB), missed deletes (deleted rows gone, can''t query them), timestamp reliability (clock skew, updates without timestamp change). Log-based CDC: read database transaction log (WAL, binlog), capture changes at source. Example: MySQL binlog, Postgres WAL, Oracle redo log. Pros: low DB impact (log already exists for replication), captures all changes (including deletes), real-time (as transactions commit), complete (every modification). Cons: DB-specific (different for each DB type), configuration required (enable binlog, WAL archival), schema changes need handling. Modern: log-based preferred (higher fidelity, lower impact), query-based for simple cases or when log access impossible. Tools: Debezium (open-source, log-based CDC for MySQL, Postgres, MongoDB, etc., streams to Kafka), AWS DMS (query or log-based), Fivetran, Airbyte. Implementation: Debezium connector reads binlog → publishes to Kafka topic → consumers process changes → load to warehouse.',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (302, 'Explain the challenges of implementing CDC from a production database. How do you minimize performance impact?',
     'Challenges: (1) Performance impact - reading transaction log adds overhead, binlog/WAL replication increases I/O, network bandwidth for streaming changes. (2) Operational complexity - configure DB for CDC (binlog format, WAL level), connector management (Debezium pods, failures), schema changes break connectors. (3) Data volume - high-throughput DB generates massive change stream, downstream consumer must keep up. (4) Initial snapshot - existing data must be loaded before CDC (full table scan, can overwhelm DB). (5) Consistency - ensure changes applied in order, handle out-of-order delivery, exactly-once processing. Minimize performance impact strategies: (1) Read from replica - point CDC connector to read replica (not primary), primary unaffected, replica handles load, eventual consistency acceptable for analytics. Caution: replica lag means delayed changes. (2) Optimize log configuration - MySQL binlog: use ROW format (captures exact changes), minimize binlog retention (disk space), tune binlog cache. Postgres WAL: set appropriate WAL level (logical for CDC), archive WAL to S3, monitor WAL disk usage. (3) Throttle CDC - rate limit change stream (if downstream can''t keep up), batch changes (micro-batches instead of per-row), prioritize critical tables (not all tables need real-time CDC). (4) Network optimization - compress change stream (reduces bandwidth), dedicated network (isolate CDC traffic), monitor network saturation. (5) Initial snapshot strategy - snapshot during off-peak hours (low DB load), use READ COMMITTED or SNAPSHOT isolation (avoid locking), parallelize snapshot (multiple connectors for different tables), incremental snapshot (if supported). (6) Schema change handling - coordinate schema changes with CDC (change DB schema → update connector → restart consumers), schema registry (Confluent Schema Registry) manages schema versions. (7) Monitoring - track replication lag (how far behind source), connector health (crashes, restarts), DB load (CPU, I/O impact), alert on issues. Debezium-specific optimizations: snapshot.mode = schema_only (skip initial data, CDC from now), heartbeat.interval (keep connection alive without overhead), poll.interval.ms (how often read log), tasks.max (parallel tasks for throughput). Best practices: test in non-production first (understand impact), start small (one table, expand), monitor continuously (early detection of issues), plan for failures (connector restarts, replication lag catchup), document runbooks.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),


    (303, 'How do you handle schema evolution in CDC pipelines? What happens when source table schema changes?',
     'Schema evolution challenges: (1) Add column - new column in source, downstream consumers unaware, may break strict schema validation. (2) Rename column - appears as drop + add, data mapping breaks. (3) Change data type - incompatible transformations (string to int), downstream parsing fails. (4) Drop column - consumers expecting column get null or error. Handling strategies: (1) Schema registry - centralized schema management (Confluent Schema Registry, AWS Glue), CDC publishes schema with each event, consumers validate against registry, version schema (v1, v2), backward/forward compatibility rules. (2) Graceful degradation - consumers ignore unknown columns (forward compatible), provide defaults for missing columns (backward compatible), log warnings but don''t crash. (3) Coordinated changes - plan schema migrations (announce changes in advance), staged rollout (update source → update CDC connector → update consumers), blue-green deployment for major changes. (4) Schema translation layer - adapter between source schema and consumer expectation, maps old column names to new, handles type conversions, decouples source from consumers. (5) Avro/Protobuf serialization - self-describing schemas (schema embedded in message), evolution rules built-in (optional fields, defaults), tooling handles compatibility checks. Debezium handling: schema.history.internal topic stores schema history, connector detects schema changes, publishes schema change events, consumers receive notification. Best practices: additive changes only when possible (add columns, dont drop), use nullable columns (avoids breaking existing events), version APIs/schemas explicitly, test schema changes in staging, monitor for compatibility errors, rollback plan ready.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (304, 'What are the different CDC patterns for syncing data to a data warehouse? Compare snapshot + incremental vs streaming.',
     'CDC to warehouse patterns: (1) Snapshot + Incremental - initial full snapshot of table, subsequent CDC captures only changes, periodically merge changes into warehouse. Workflow: full snapshot → load to staging → swap staging with production, CDC stream → accumulate changes in delta table → periodic merge (hourly, daily) into main table. Pros: simple, batch-friendly, warehouse optimized for bulk loads. Cons: latency (changes batched), complexity in merge logic (upsert). Use: acceptable latency (hours), large tables, cost-sensitive. (2) Streaming CDC - continuous stream of changes, apply to warehouse in real-time or micro-batches. Workflow: CDC → Kafka → stream processor (Flink, Spark Streaming) → warehouse (continuous INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE). Pros: low latency (seconds), real-time analytics. Cons: expensive (warehouse compute always on), complex (stateful processing), write amplification. Use: real-time dashboards, SLA < 5min. (3) Log-based incremental - use database WAL offsets to track progress, resume from last checkpoint, no full snapshot needed (or minimal). Workflow: Debezium maintains offset, reads WAL from last offset, streams changes. Pros: efficient, no full scan, automatic resume. Cons: WAL retention limits (can''t go too far back), initial backfill still needed. Implementation details: Merge strategy (upsert) - use MERGE statement or DELETE + INSERT (Snowflake, BigQuery support MERGE), match on primary key, UPDATE if exists else INSERT, handle deletes (soft delete or hard delete). Idempotency - CDC events may duplicate (Kafka at-least-once), use event IDs orsequence numbers, deduplicate in warehouse (window function to keep latest). Ordering - maintain order per key (row), use timestamp or WAL offset, handle out-of-order (late arriving updates). Partitioning - partition warehouse table by date or change type, optimize for queries and merges. Performance optimization - batch micro-batches (collect 1 minute of changes, apply together), use columnar format for staging (Parquet), parallel processing (partition by key,process concurrently). Tools combination: Debezium → Kafka → Kafka Connect Snowflake Sink (streaming), Debezium → Kafka → Spark Structured Streaming → Delta Lake (micro-batch), Fivetran/Hevo (managed, handles CDC patterns). Modern approach: use lake house with ACID (Delta, Iceberg, Hudi), supports efficient upserts, time travel for debugging, streaming and batch in one platform.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (305, 'Your e-commerce platform needs real-time inventory sync from PostgreSQL to Snowflake for analytics. Inventory updates happen 1000/sec during peak. Design a CDC solution. How do you ensure exactly-once semantics, handle backpressure, and maintain low latency (<30sec from DB update to Snowflake)?',
     'Requirements analysis: 1000 updates/sec peak (high throughput), exactly-once (critical for inventory accuracy), < 30sec latency (real-time analytics), PostgreSQL → Snowflake. Architecture design: (1) CDC Source - PostgreSQL with logical replication, enable WAL (wal_level=logical), create publication for inventory table. (2) CDC Connector - Debezium PostgreSQL connector, reads WAL via replication slot, publishes to Kafka (resilient buffer), exactly-once with transactional writes to Kafka. (3) Stream Buffer - Kafka topic (inventory-changes), partitioned by product_id (maintains order per product), replication factor 3 (durability), retention 7 days (allows replay). (4) Stream Processor - Kafka Streams or Flink, consumes from Kafka, aggregates micro-batches (10 sec windows), deduplicates (idempotent processing), prepares MERGE statements. (5) Warehouse Loader - Snowflake Snowpipe (auto-ingestion) OR Kafka Connect Snowflake Sink, batched writes (optimize for Snowflake, dozens of rows per transaction is inefficient), exactly-once via Snowflake transactional staging. Exactly-once semantics implementation: (1) Debezium → Kafka - idempotent producer (enable.idempotence=true), transactional writes (guarantees exactly-once to Kafka), deduplication based on WAL offset (monotonic, prevents duplicates). (2) Kafka → Processor - consumer groups with offset management, read committed isolation (only see Committed Kafka records), checkpoint offsets after processing (Kafka Streams state stores, Flink checkpoints). (3) Processor → Snowflake - staging tables (write to temp table first), MERGE into final table (idempotent, multiple executions safe), transaction IDs tracked (skip already applied batches). Backpressure handling: (1) Kafka as buffer - 1000/sec easily absorbed by Kafka (handles MB/sec), consumer processes at comfortable pace, producer won''t be blocked. (2) Parallel processing - partition by product_id, scale consumers to match partitions (10-20 partitions, multiple consumer instances), each handles subset of products. (3) Batching - accumulate 10 seconds of changes (10K updates) → single MERGE operation, reduces Snowflake API calls, improves throughput. (4) Auto-scaling - monitor consumer lag (Kafka consumer lag metric), scale up consumers if lag > threshold (Kubernetes HPA), scale down during low traffic. (5) Circuit breaker - if Snowflake slow/down (backpressure from sink), pause further processing temporarily, retry with exponential backoff, alert on continued issues. Latency optimization (target < 30sec): Breakdown: CDC capture (< 1sec), Kafka buffering (< 1sec), Processing (< 10sec), Snowflake load (< 15sec), Buffer (< 3sec). Optimizations: (1) Reduce batch window - 10sec batches (not 1min), trade-off: more frequent Snowflake writes (cost) vs lower latency. (2) Snowflake Snowpipe - near real-time ingestion, auto-ingest from S3 (processor writes to S3, Snowpipe loads), < 1min latency typically, but cost per file. Alternative: Kafka Connector direct to Snowflake, avoids S3 hop. (3) Efficient MERGE - partition Snowflake table by date, cluster by product_id (faster lookups), materialized views for hot queries (pre-aggregate). (4) Parallel writes - multiple Kafka Connect tasks write concurrently, Snowflake handles concurrency well. Monitoring and alerting: (1) Latency tracking - emit timestamp at each stage (DB update time, Kafka publish time, process time, Snowflake write time), calculate end-to-end latency, alert if > 30sec p95. (2) Throughput - monitor events/sec at each stage, detect bottlenecks (which stage slowing down?). (3) Lag - Debezium replication slot lag (WAL bytes behind), Kafka consumer lag (messages behind), Snowflake staging data age. (4) Error rates - CDC connector failures, Kafka producer errors, Snowflake load errors, automatic retry vs alert. Failure recovery: (1) Debezium failure - restart connector, resumes from last WAL offset (no data loss), catch-up lag (may spike latency during recovery). (2) Kafka broker failure - replication ensures durability, consumer switches to replica, transparent. (3) Snowflake unavailable - Kafka buffers changes (7 day retention plenty of runway), resume once Snowflake back, catch-up processing. (4) Network partition - retry logic with backoff, eventual consistency once resolved. Alternative architecture considerations: If latency requirement relaxes (hours acceptable): use Fivetran/Airbyte managed CDC (simpler operations), batch-oriented with scheduled syncs. If volume grows (10K/sec): consider change to streaming architecture with Flink (more complex but handles higher scale), or sharded Snowflake with distributed writes. Testing strategy: (1) Load test - simulate 1000 updates/sec in staging, measure latency distribution, validate exactly-once (no duplicates, no missing events). (2) Failure testing - kill Debezium mid-stream, kill Kafka broker, Snowflake throttling, verify recovery and data consistency. (3) Backfill test - large historical load (million records), ensure system handles spike, measure catch-up time. Cost optimization: Snowflake compute costs (keep warehouse running for continuous load), consider suspend/resume with scheduled micro-batches if cost concern, Kafka retention tuned (7 days vs 30 days, balance durability and cost), S3 storage if using Snowpipe (cleanup old files). Expected results: End-to-end latency p95 < 25sec (under 30sec SLA), throughput sustained at 1000/sec peak, exactly-once guarantees validated (inventory counts match), zero data loss scenarios, cost-effective at scale.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 62: Data Partitioning Strategies (5 questions)
    (306, 'What is data partitioning? Why is it important in distributed systems and data warehouses?',
     'Data partitioning: dividing large dataset into smaller segments (partitions) stored separately, each partition manageable independently. Types: horizontal (rows split), vertical (columns split). Why important: (1) Performance - query scans only relevant partitions (partition pruning), example: query for Jan 2024 data only scans Jan partition. (2) Scalability - distribute partitions across nodes, parallel processing (each node handles subset). (3) Management - easier to backup/restore/archive partitions, delete old data by dropping partition (instant). (4) Cost - move old partitions to cheaper storage (S3 Glacier), keep hot data on fast storage. Common partitioning schemes: (1) Range partitioning - by date (most common: daily, monthly), by numeric range (customer ID 1-1000, 1001-2000). Example: sales_2024_01, sales_2024_02 partitions. Pros: natural for time-series, easy pruning. Cons: uneven sizes (some days more data), hotspotting (recent partitions heavily queried). (2) Hash partitioning - hash function distributes rows evenly. Example: hash(user_id) mod 10 determines partition. Pros: even distribution, no hotspots. Cons: can''t prune by range (hash loses order), reshard complex. (3) List partitioning - by discrete values (region: US, EU, ASIA), by category. Pros: logical grouping, business-aligned. Cons: uneven if values skewed. (4) Composite - combine schemes (partition by date, sub-partition by region). Implementation: Database level (PostgreSQL partitioning, MySQL partitions), data warehouse (Snowflake clustering, BigQuery partitioning), file system (Hive partitioned parquet in S3). Best practice: partition by most common filter, avoid over-partitioning (too many small partitions overhead), monitor partition sizes (rebalance if skewed).',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (307, 'Compare partition pruning vs full table scan. How do databases optimize partition pruning?',
     'Full table scan: query reads every row in table, slow for large tables, high I/O cost. Example: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date = ''2024-01-15'' scans entire orders table (100M rows). Partition pruning: query optimizer determines which partitions needed, scans only those partitions, dramatically faster. Example: if orders partitioned by month, same query scans only Jan 2024 partition (3M rows, 97% reduction). Performance difference: full scan might take minutes, pruned scan seconds. Optimization techniques databases use: (1) Metadata analysis - optimizer reads partition metadata (min/max values per partition, bloom filters, statistics), compares query predicates to metadata, eliminates partitions that can''t satisfy predicate. Example: query WHERE date = ''2024-06-15'' eliminates all partitions except Jun 2024. (2) Static pruning - at query plan time, before execution, predicates known at compile (hard-coded dates), deterministic elimination. (3) Dynamic pruning - at execution time, when predicates depend on runtime values (subqueries, joins). Example: WHERE date IN (SELECT date FROM other_table), must execute subquery first, then prune. (4) Partition-wise joins - if two tables partitioned identically (same key, same ranges), optimizer joins corresponding partitions separately, parallel processing, no shuffle. Example: sales and inventory both partitioned by date, join on date processes each day independently. Requirements for effective pruning: (1) Partition key in WHERE clause - query must filter on partition column, optimizer can''t prune if no filter. (2) Simple predicates - explicit comparisons work (date = X, date BETWEEN X AND Y), complex functions may prevent pruning (WHERE YEAR(date) = 2024 might not prune, depends on optimizer). (3) Partition metadata current - stale statistics mislead optimizer, run ANALYZE regularly. Tools visibility: EXPLAIN shows partition pruning (Postgres: Partitions scanned, Snowflake: partitions pruned), validate queries prune effectively. Anti-patterns: function on partition column (WHERE DATE(timestamp_column) = X), partition column hidden in complex expression, missing partition filter entirely.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (308, 'What is data skew in partitioning? How does it impact performance and how do you detect and fix it?',
     'Data skew: uneven distribution of data across partitions, some partitions much larger than others, causes hotspots (overloaded partitions while others idle). Causes: (1) Range partitioning with natural skew - example: e-commerce orders by date, Black Friday partition 100x larger than average day. (2) Hash partitioning with bad key - example: hash on nullable column (all nulls go to one partition), low cardinality key. (3) List partitioning with skewed categories - example: partition by country, USA has 80% of data. Performance impacts: (1) Slow queries - scanning large partition takes long, even with pruning. (2) Uneven parallelism - 10 partitions, one has 90% data, 9 workers idle while 1 overloaded. (3) Memory pressure - large partition doesn''t fit in memory, spills to disk. (4) Load balancing - writes concentrated on one partition (hot partition). Detection: (1) Partition size metrics - query partition sizes (row count, bytes), visualize distribution (histogram), identify outliers (partition 10x larger than average). SQL: SELECT partition_name, row_count FROM information_schema.partitions ORDER BY row_count DESC; (2) Query performance variance - same query type fast on some partitions, slow on others, indicates skew. (3) Resource monitoring - CPU/memory usage uneven across nodes (one node saturated). Fixing strategies: (1) Re-partition with better key - change partition column (date → hour for high volume days), add composite partition (date + region for better granularity), hash if natural ordering doesn''t matter. (2) SaltingScatter skewed partition across multiple physical partitions. Example: Black Friday orders split into black_friday_1, black_friday_2...black_friday_10 (10 sub-partitions), query unions across salted partitions. Implementation: add salt column (random 0-9), partition by (date, salt). (3) List splitting - multiple partitions for large categories, single partition for small categories. Example: USA_partition_1, USA_partition_2, Others_partition. (4) Dynamic partitioning - create partitions on-demand based on data volume, split large partitions when threshold exceeded. (5) Data sampling/compression - for historical partitions (rarely queried), aggregate or compress, reduce size. Modern approaches: adaptive partitioning (Snowflake micr-partitions auto-split), auto-optimize (Databricks optimizes partition sizes), statistics-based re-partition (Spark AQE adjusts at runtime). Best practices: monitor partition sizes regularly, benchmark on real data before production, allow for growth (design for 10x future volume), document partition strategy.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (309, 'Explain partition exchange vs partition rebuild. When would you use each?',
     'Partition exchange: swap partition with external table, metadata-only operation (no data movement), instantaneous. Use case: loading bulk data efficiently. Example: create staging table with new month data, validate data quality, exchange staging into partitioned table as new partition, old partition metadata updated. Benefit: zero downtime (atomic switch), fast (seconds regardless of size), rollback easy (exchange back). Steps: CREATE TABLE staging_feb AS SELECT ...; -- validate data in staging, ALTER TABLE orders EXCHANGE PARTITION feb_2024 WITH TABLE staging_feb; Constraints: tables must have identical schema, indexes, constraints (or constraints disabled). Partition rebuild: reconstruct partition from scratch, rewrite data physically, expensive. Use case: defragmentation, storage optimization, change storage properties. Example: partition has many deletes (fragmented), rebuild reclaims space and reorganizes. Benefit: optimized storage, fresh statistics, fix corruption. Steps: ALTER TABLE orders REBUILD PARTITION jan_2024; Risk: locks partition (reads blocked), takes time (rewrite all data), resource intensive. Comparison: Exchange (metadata-only, fast, data loading), Rebuild (data rewrite, slow, maintenance). Use partition exchange for: (1) Bulk loads - load large batch (millions of rows), stage and validate, exchange into production (instant). (2) Zero-downtime schema changes - create new partition with new schema, ETL data to new format, exchange. (3) Archival - exchange old partition with archived table, move to cold storage. (4) Testing - exchange staging data in/out for testing, non-disruptive. Use partition rebuild for: (1) Reclaim space - many DELETEs/UPDATEs left holes, rebuild compacts. (2) Change storage - move partition to different tablespace, change compression settings. (3) Fix corruption - rare but rebuild can repair damaged partition. (4) Update statistics - rebuild forces stat regeneration (though ANALYZE is lighter). Alternatives modern: (1) Online partition move - some databases support non-locking moves. (2) CREATE TABLE AS SELECT - explicit rebuild into new partition. (3) Vacuum/Optimize - lightweight space reclaim (Postgres VACUUM, Databricks OPTIMIZE). Best practice: prefer exchange for data operations (fast, safe), use rebuild sparingly (maintenance windows, scheduled), test exchange in staging first, monitor rebuild progress (can take hours).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (310, 'You have a 50TB events table in Snowflake partitioned by date (daily partitions). Queries filtering by user_id are slow because user_id is not the partition key, resulting in full table scans across all date partitions. How would you optimize for both date and user_id queries without duplicating data?',
     'Challenge: single partition key (date), but queries on multiple dimensions (date, user_id), can''t partition by both efficiently, data duplication expensive (50TB × 2 = 100TB). Current state analysis: date partitions work for date queries (pruning effective), user_id queries scan all dates (partition pruning fails, 50TB scan). Goal: optimize both without full duplication. Multi-dimensional optimization strategies: (1) Clustering keys (Snowflake-specific solution): Snowflake micro-partitions auto-manage, add cluster keys for frequent query patterns, ALTER TABLE events CLUSTER BY (user_id, event_date); Effect: Snowflake co-locates rows with similar user_id + date, user_id queries scan fewer micro-partitions (pruning on cluster key), hybrid optimization for both dimensions. Tradeoff: re-clustering costs (Snowflake auto-clusters, uses compute credits), not as effective as dedicated partitions but good middle ground. Expected: 50TB → scan 500GB for specific user (100x reduction). (2) Materialized Aggregate Views: For common user_id queries (analytics, not raw events), create materialized views pre-aggregated by user, example: CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW user_summary AS SELECT user_id, date, COUNT(*), SUM(value) FROM events GROUP BY user_id, date; View is tiny compared to raw (millions of rows vs billions), queries hit view not raw table. Limitation: works for aggregates, not raw event drill-down. (3) Secondary Index / Search Optimization (if supported): Snowflake Search Optimization Service, create search optimization on user_id, ALTER TABLE events ADD SEARCH OPTIMIZATION ON EQUALITY(user_id); Builds inverted index-like structure, accelerates point lookups (WHERE user_id = X). Cost: storage for index + maintenance. Benefit: fast user lookups without scan. (4) Partitioned Materialized Views by user_id: Create second table/view partitioned differently, CREATE TABLE events_by_user AS SELECT * FROM events; ALTER TABLE events_by_user CLUSTER BY (user_id); Keep date-partitioned for date queries, user-partitioned for user queries. Tradeoff: storage cost (now 100TB total), but specialized access. Mitigation: use compute/storage separation (Snowflake), storage cheap, compute only when queried. (5) Hybrid Partitioning with Sub-partitions: Partition by date, sub-cluster by user_id, example: daily partitions (365 partitions), each daily partition clustered by user_id internally. Date queries prune to relevant days, user_id queries scan fewer micro-partitions within relevant days. (6) Bloom Filters / Partition Metadata: Enhance partition metadata with min/max user_id per partition, WHERE user_id = X checks metadata, skips partitions not containing user. Some databases auto-create (Snowflake micro-partition metadata), others require manual (Hive with stats). Recommendation for Snowflake: Implement clustering + search optimization + materialized views (where applicable). Detailed implementation: Step 1 - Add clustering key: ALTER TABLE events CLUSTER BY (event_date, user_id); Snowflake reorders micro-partitions (background process), queries benefit from both date and user_id pruning. Step 2 - Enable search optimization for user_id: ALTER TABLE events ADD SEARCH OPTIMIZATION ON EQUALITY(user_id); Point lookups on user_id accelerated. Step 3 - Create materialized views for common dashboards: CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW daily_user_metrics AS SELECT user_id, DATE(event_timestamp) as date, COUNT(*) as event_count, SUM(value) as total_value FROM events GROUP BY user_id, DATE(event_timestamp); Dashboards query view (fast) not raw table. Step 4 - Monitor and tune: Check clustering depth (ALTER TABLE events RECLUSTER if depth high), monitor query  performance (QUERY_HISTORY), adjust clustering order if needed (most selective column first). Expected results: Date queries: scan only relevant dates (already optimized), 365x pruning potential. User_id queries: clustering reduces scan from 50TB to < 1TB (50x improvement), search optimization further accelerates. Mixed queries (date + user_id): best of both (date pruning + user_id clustering), seconds instead of minutes. Cost considerations: Clustering maintenance cost (auto-recluster uses compute), search optimization storage overhead (< 10% typically), materialized view storage (depends on aggregation, typically 1-5% of raw), balance cost vs query performance (measure $$$ spent clustering vs query compute savings). Alternative if cost prohibitive: Partition exchange pattern - archive old data (> 1 year) to cheaper storage, keep hot data (recent 3 months) in optimized table (smaller, easier to cluster/index), queries on old data slower but acceptable (rare). Testing approach: Benchmark before optimizations (user_id query execution time, data scanned), enable clustering + wait for convergence (can take hours for 50TB), run same queries, measure improvement, iterate if needed (adjust clustering keys). Success criteria: user_id queries < 10 sec (vs minutes before), data scanned reduced 90%+, clustering depth stable (< 4), cost increase acceptable (< 20% total warehouse cost).',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 63: Real-time vs Batch Processing (5 questions)
    (311, 'What are the key differences between batch and stream processing? When would you choose one over the other?',
     'Batch processing: processes bounded datasets at scheduled intervals, high throughput, high latency. Examples: nightly ETL, monthly reports, model training. Characteristics: input is complete finite dataset, processed in chunks (batches), optimize for throughput (process millions efficiently), eventual consistency (data updated periodically). Stream processing: processes unbounded data continuously, low latency, event-by-event or micro-batch. Examples: fraud detection, real-time dashboards, alerting. Characteristics: infinite input stream, processed as events arrive, optimize for latency (milliseconds-seconds), near real-time consistency. Key differences: Latency - batch: minutes to hours, stream: milliseconds to seconds. Data availability - batch: all data available upfront, stream: incremental arrival. Processing model - batch: map-reduce over full dataset, stream: stateful operators per event. Resource usage - batch: burst compute (job runs then idle), stream: continuous compute. Cost - batch: cheaper (ephemeral resources), stream: more expensive (always on). Use batch for: historical analysis, complex ML training, large aggregations not time-sensitive, cost-sensitive workloads, simple operations over huge datasets. Use stream for: operational metrics, time-sensitive actions (fraud blocking), event-driven architectures, continuous analytics, when business needs real-time insight. Hybrid approaches: Lambda architecture (both batch + stream, merge results), Kappa architecture (stream only, replay for batch-like), micro-batching (Spark Streaming processes small batches frequently, middle ground). Decision factors: business SLA (can wait hours or need seconds?), data volume (TB daily suggests batch, unlimited stream suggests stream), infrastructure (existing Hadoop cluster suggests batch, Kafka infrastructure suggests stream), cost budget (batch cheaper for same volume).',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (312, 'Explain micro-batching in Spark Streaming. How does it differ from true streaming in Flink?',
     'Micro-batching (Spark Streaming DStreams): divides continuous stream into small batches (seconds), processes each batch as mini-RDD, batch processing model applied repeatedly. Example: 2-second micro-batches, stream collected for 2 sec → process as RDD → output → repeat. Pros: leverage existing batch API (RDDs), natural checkpointing (per batch), simple model (batch mindset). Cons: latency (minimum equals batch interval, 2 sec micro-batch = ≥2 sec latency), not truly event-at-a-time, batch interval tuning required. True streaming (Flink): each event processed individually through operators, continuous data flow, no artificial batching. Events flow through topology as they arrive. Pros: lowest latency (milliseconds), natural for stateful event-driven logic, powerful windowing and event time. Cons: complexity (harder mental model), checkpointing more complex (async snapshots). Spark Structured Streaming: newer Spark API, abstracts micro-batching with streaming DataFrame API, continuous processing mode available (experimental, more like Flink). Comparison: Latency - Flink lower (milliseconds), Spark DStreams higher (seconds). Programming model - Flink streaming-first, Spark batch-first (applied to micro-batches). State management - Flink operator state (fine-grained), Spark RDD state (batch-level). Event time - Flink native watermarking, Spark added later (Structured Streaming). Ecosystem - Spark broader (ML, SQL, batch unified), Flink streaming-specialized. Use Spark Streaming for: existing Spark investment, batch + stream in same codebase, latency > 1-2 seconds acceptable, simpler mental model. Use Flink for: ultra-low latency requirements (<100ms), complex event processing, sophisticated windowing, dedicated streaming. Modern trend: Structured Streaming narrowing gap, Flink gaining adoption for latency-critical, both viable depending on requirements.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (313, 'What is event time vs processing time? Why does it matter and how do you handle late-arriving events?',
     'Event time: timestamp when event actually occurred (embedded in data). Example: sensor reading at 10:00 AM, but transmission delayed. Processing time: timestamp when system processes event (wall-clock). Example: reading arrives and processed at 10:05 AM. Why difference matters: network delays, system downtime, backfilling historical data cause processing time ≠ event time. Using processing time for windowing gives incorrect results (events grouped by when processed, not when occurred). Example pitfall: count events per minute using processing time, network hiccup delays events, minute window undercounted. Using event time gives correct business logic. Handling late events: (1) Watermarks - system estimates "events before time T have all arrived", allows closing windows despite delays. Example: watermark = max event time - 5 minutes (assume events arrive within 5 min). Window closes when watermark passes window end. (2) Allowed lateness - accept events within lateness threshold after watermark. Example: window 10:00-10:01, watermark at 10:06 (passing window), but allow 10 min lateness, events arriving until 10:11 still included (window updated). (3) Side outputs - very late events (beyond lateness) routed to separate stream for manual handling. (4) Reprocessing - for critical correctness, reprocess past windows when late data significant. Strategies comparison: Ignore late data - simple but inaccurate. Trigger on every event - accurate but expensive (many updates). Watermark + allowed lateness - balance accuracy and efficiency (most common). Infinite allowed lateness - perfectly accurate but windows never close (impractical). Implementation: Flink - built-in event time and watermarks, Spark Structured Streaming - event time in DataFrame API, Kafka Streams - event time and grace period. Best practice: use event time for business logic (correctness), tune watermarks based on data latency profile (observe 99th percentile delay), design downstream to handle window updates (idempotent writes), monitor late events (too many suggests infrastructure issue).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (314, 'How do you achieve exactly-once semantics in stream processing? Explain the challenges and solutions.',
     'Exactly-once: each event processed exactly one time, no duplicates, no losses. Challenges: (1) At-least-once vs at-most-once - at-least-once (acknowledge after processing, failure before ack causes reprocessing, duplicates), at-most-once (acknowledge before processing, failure after ack causes loss). (2) Distributed failures - stream processor crashes mid-processing, network partitions, message broker duplicates. (3) Side effects - writing to external systems (databases, files), idempotent writes needed. Exactly-once solutions: (1) Idempotent operations - design processing to be idempotent (can execute multiple times safely). Example: SET value = X (idempotent), INCREMENT value (not idempotent, needs dedup). Use unique message IDs, check if already processed. (2) Transactional processing - combine message acknowledgment + state update + output in single transaction. Kafka Transactions achieves this: begin transaction, read from input topic, process + update state, write to output topic, commit transaction (atomic). Failure before commit = roll back everything (exactly-once). (3) Checkpointing + replay - periodic consistent snapshots of state, failure → restore from checkpoint, replay from checkpoint offset, deterministic replay ensures same results. Flink exactly-once: distributed snapshots (Chandy-Lamport algorithm), barrier alignment across sources. (4) Two-phase commit - for external sinks (databases), prepare phase (write to staging), commit phase (make visible), both phases must succeed. Distributed transaction protocol. (5) Deduplication at sink - sink detects duplicate writes (hash message,check if seen), ignores duplicates, guarantees exact effect even if sent twice. Trade-offs: Exactly-once more complex (state management, transactions), higher latency (coordination overhead), not all sinks support (file writes hard to make transactional). At-least-once simpler but requires idempotent design. Real-world: Kafka Streams + Kafka - exactly-once producer/consumer, Flink + transactional sinks - exactly-once end-to-end, Spark Structured Streaming - idempotent writes to sinks. Best practices: prefer exactly-once for critical data (financial, inventory), design idempotent when possible (easier than transactions), test failure scenarios (kill processes mid-stream, verify no duplicates/loss), understand guarantees per  tool (Kafka producer exactly-once to Kafka, but sink may be at-least-once if not transactional).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (315, 'Your company wants to move from nightly batch processing to real-time analytics. Current batch job processes 500GB daily (customer clickstream) with complex joins and aggregations, taking 3 hours to complete. Business wants insights available within 5 minutes of events occurring. Design a migration strategy. What are the risks and how do you minimize them? How do you handle the transition period where both systems run in parallel?',
     'Migration challenge: batch (3-hour job, complex logic, proven) → stream (5-min latency, unproven complexity, operational overhead). Current state: nightly batch (Spark/Hive?), 500GB daily ≈ 6MB/sec average (50K events/sec if 100KB/event), complex joins (dimension tables, enrichments), aggregations (summary tables, metrics). Target state: stream processing < 5 min latency (near real-time dashboards, operational decisions). Migration strategy framework: Phase 1 - Assessment and Planning (Weeks 1-2): (1) Decompose batch job - break into logical stages (extract, clean, join, aggregate, load), identify data dependencies (which datasets needed?), map business logic (SQL to streaming). (2) Evaluate streaming tech - Flink (true streaming, low latency), Spark Structured Streaming (familiarity if using Spark), managed options (Databricks, AWS Kinesis Analytics). Decision criteria: latency requirements, team expertise, budget. (3) Identify risks - data loss/duplicates (exactly-once requirement?), logic gaps (batch operations hard in streaming, like full outer joins), performance unknowns (can handle 6MB/sec?), operational complexity (24/7 monitoring). (4) Dual-write strategy - run batch and stream in parallel (safety net), compare outputs for correctness, gradual cutover. Phase 2 - Prototype and Validate (Weeks 3-6): (1) Build streaming MVP - select simple subset of logic (one dashboard worth), implement in Flink/Spark Streaming, test with sampled data (10% volume). (2) Data source migration - batch reads from data lake (S3/HDFS), stream needs event source (Kafka topic), setup CDC or app instrumentation to Kafka, backfill recent history to Kafka (replay capability). (3) Complex logic handling - Joins: dimension tables (broadcast joins, cache in stream processor), fact-to-fact joins (windowed joins if temporal), full scans (materialize dimensions). Aggregations: windowed aggregations (tumbling 5-min windows), session windows if user-centric, state management (Flink rocksDB, Spark state store). (4) Output comparison - both batch and stream write outputs, diff checker compares results (row counts, sums, samples), identify discrepancies, iterate until match > 99%. Phase 3 - Parallel Run (Weeks 7-10): (1) Full implementation - complete all batch logic in streaming, handle edge cases discovered in prototype, optimize performance (partitioning, parallelism, state size). (2) Dual infrastructure - run both systems producing same outputs, batch writes to *_batch tables, stream writes to *_stream tables, downstream consumers still use batch (no disruption). (3) Monitoring and alerting - latency tracking (event-to-output time), throughput metrics (events/sec processed), data quality checks (same aggregates as batch?), resource usage (CPU, memory, Kafka lag). (4) Stress testing - peak load simulation (Black Friday traffic spike), failure scenarios (broker down, processor crash), backlog recovery (Kafka lag catchup). Phase 4 - Gradual Cutover (Weeks 11-14): (1) Low-risk tables first - cut over non-critical dashboards to stream, monitor for issues, gather feedback, critical reports still on batch. (2) Comparison period - stream outputs become primary, but batch still runs (validation), daily comparison reports (any divergence?), investigate and fix discrepancies. (3) Full cutover - switch all consumers to stream tables, deprecate batch job (but keep code for emergency), decommission batch after 30-day confidence period. (4) Rollback plan - if critical issue, revert consumers to batch tables, batch job still available (can restart), fix stream issue without customer impact. Risks and mitigations: Risk 1: Data loss/duplicates - Mitigation: exactly-once semantics (Kafka transactions, Flink checkpointing), idempotent design (dedup), extensive testing. Risk 2: Performance degradation under load - Mitigation: load testing before production, auto-scaling (Kubernetes for Flink), backpressure monitoring (Kafka lag alerts), over-provision initially (scale down later). Risk 3: Logic bugs (streaming behaves differently) - Mitigation: parallel run with comparison (catch discrepancies), comprehensive unit tests (test logic in isolation), gradual rollout (errors impact subset). Risk 4: Operational complexity - Mitigation: managed services reduce overhead (Confluent Cloud, Databricks), robust monitoring (Datadog, Grafana), runbooks for common issues (lag, failures), 24/7 on-call initially. Risk 5: Cost explosion - Mitigation: cost projection (estimate compute hours), rightsizing (dont over-provision long-term), optimize resource usage (tune parallelism, batch size), compare batch vs stream cost. Risk 6: Team skill gap - Mitigation: training (Flink/Kafka courses), hire expertise (streaming engineer), partner with vendor (Confluent, Databricks support), start simple (gain confidence). Parallel run logistics: Batch schedule - keep nightly batch running (3-hour window, completes by 6 AM). Stream continuous - Flink job always on, 5-min latency, results available real-time. Data sources - Kafka topic for stream (events land continuously), same events also batched to S3 for batch job (redundancy), validate both see same data. Output reconciliation - automated daily check: SELECT SUM(metric), COUNT(*) FROM batch_table vs stream_table, alert if diff > 1%, human review and fix. Cutover checklist: [ ] Stream latency < 5min consistently for 2 weeks, [ ] Data quality checks passing >99%, [ ] No critical bugs in production, [ ] Team comfortable operating stream infrastructure, [ ] Rollback plan tested (can switch back in < 1 hour), [ ] Stakeholder approval (business accepts stream outputs). Post-migration: Monitor latency continuously (alert if > 5 min), cost optimization (tune resources, eliminate waste), iterate on logic (streaming unlocks new possibilities, real-time models), decommission batch (free up resources). Success metrics: Latency: p95 < 5 minutes (vs 3-12 hours batch), Availability: > 99.9% uptime (streaming SLA), Data quality: 100% match with historical batch (during parallel run), Cost: stream cost < 2x batch cost (acceptable for real-time benefit), Team confidence: on-call incidents < 1/week after stabilization. Expected timeline: 14 weeks from start to full cutover (aggressive but achievable), 4-6 months for optimization and confidence building, batch decommissioned after 6 months total.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true);

-- End of Data Engineering section (Topics 51-63, Questions 251-315)


-- ============================================================================
-- MOBILE DEVELOPMENT TOPICS (Topics 64-75, Questions 316-375)
-- ============================================================================

    -- Topic 64: iOS Development (5 questions)
    (316, 'What is the difference between frame and bounds in UIView? When would you use each?',
     'Frame: position and size of view in its superview''s coordinate system, CGRect with origin relative to parent. Example: frame = (x:50, y:100, width:200, height:100) means view is 50 points right, 100 points down from parent origin. Bounds: position and size in its own coordinate system, origin usually (0,0), used for drawing content within view. Example: bounds = (x:0, y:0, width:200, height:100). Key difference: frame for positioning relative to parent, bounds for internal content and transformations. Use frame to: position subview within parent, determine view location in parent. Use bounds to: draw content (drawRect uses bounds), scroll content (change bounds.origin to scroll without moving frame), after transformations (rotation/scale changes frame but not bounds). Example: rotating view 45° changes frame (bounding box larger) but bounds unchanged (still 200x100). Best practice: use Auto Layout constraints instead of manually setting frames when possible, use bounds for custom drawing and scroll views.',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (317, 'Explain the iOS app lifecycle. What happens in each state transition?',
     'App states: Not Running (app not launched or terminated), Inactive (in foreground but not receiving events, brief transition state), Active (in foreground, receiving events), Background (executing code but not visible), Suspended (in background, not executing, can be terminated by system). State transitions and callbacks: (1) Launch: Not Running → Inactive → Active, application:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions: (setup, restore state), applicationDidBecomeActive: (UI refresh, resume timers). (2) Home button press: Active → Inactive → Background → Suspended, applicationWillResignActive: (pause tasks, disable timers), applicationDidEnterBackground: (save data, release resources), have ~5 seconds before suspended. (3) Return to app: Suspended → Background → Inactive → Active, applicationWillEnterForeground: (undo what you did in didEnterBackground), applicationDidBecomeActive: (refresh UI, restart tasks). (4) Termination: any state → Not Running, applicationWillTerminate: (save data, cleanup), not always called (e.g., force quit, crash, suspended apps killed without notification). Scene-based lifecycle (iOS 13+): UIScene delegates, scene:willConnectToSession:, sceneDidBecomeActive:, sceneWillResignActive:, manages multiple windows. Best practices: save state immediately in didEnterBackground (don''t rely on willTerminate), gracefully handle interruptions (phone call = Inactive), test all transitions (ensure app survives being suspended and killed).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (318, 'What is the difference between strong, weak, and unowned references in Swift? How do you prevent retain cycles?',
     'Reference types: (1) Strong (default): increases retain count, object stays alive as long as strong reference exists. (2) Weak: doesn''t increase retain count, automatically set to nil when object deallocated, optional type. (3) Unowned: doesn''t increase retain count, like weak but assumes object always exists (non-optional), crashes if accessed after deallocation. Retain cycle: two objects strongly reference each other, neither ever deallocated (memory leak). Example: class Parent { var child: Child? }; class Child { var parent: Parent? }; parent.child = child; child.parent = parent; cycle created. Preventing retain cycles: (1) Use weak for delegates: protocol SomeDelegate: AnyObject {}; class SomeClass { weak var delegate: SomeDelegate? }, delegate doesn''t own the class. (2) Use weak in closures for self: { [weak self] in self?.doSomething() }, avoids capturing self strongly. (3) Use unowned for closures that always execute while self exists: { [unowned self] in self.doSomething() }. (4) Break cycle manually: parent.child = nil before releasing. When to choose: weak for optionals that can be nil (delegates, parent references), unowned for non-optionals that you know will outlive the reference (closure that executes during object lifetime), strong for ownership (retain objects you need). Common patterns: delegates weak (view doesn''t own delegate), parent-child (child weak references parent), closure capture lists ([weak self] for async operations). Best practice: use weak by default for references that could cause cycles, use Instruments Leaks tool to detect retain cycles.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (319, 'Explain the iOS Grand Central Dispatch (GCD). How do you use dispatch queues for concurrency?',
     'Grand Central Dispatch (GCD): Apple''s concurrency framework, manages thread pool, dispatch tasks to queues. Queue types: (1) Serial queue - executes tasks one at a time in order (FIFO). (2) Concurrent queue - executes multiple tasks simultaneously (order starts FIFO but completion varies). (3) Main queue - serial queue on main thread, UI updates must happen here. (4) Global queues - system-provided concurrent queues with different QoS. Quality of Service (QoS) priorities: userInteractive (highest, UI-blocking), userInitiated (user-requested task), utility (long-running, progress indicator), background (lowest, pre-fetching). Usage patterns: Dispatch async to background: DispatchQueue.global(qos: .userInitiated).async { /* heavy work */ }, returns immediately, doesn''t block caller. Dispatch back to main for UI: DispatchQueue.main.async { /* update UI */ }. Synchronous dispatch: queue.sync { /* blocks until complete */ }, use sparingly (can deadlock). Creating custom queues: let serialQueue = DispatchQueue(label: "com.app.serial"); let concurrentQueue = DispatchQueue(label: "com.app.concurrent", attributes: .concurrent). Dispatch groups for coordination: let group = DispatchGroup(); multiple async tasks with group.enter() / group.leave(); group.notify when all complete. Barriers for reader-writer: queue.async(flags: .barrier) { write }, ensures exclusive access. Common pitfalls: deadlock (main queue sync on main thread), race conditions (concurrent queue without synchronization), updating UI off main thread (crash or undefined behavior). Best practices: use async for network/disk I/O, always update UI on main thread, use serial queues for mutable shared state, prefer OperationQueue for cancelable complex operations.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (320, 'Your iOS app is experiencing frequent crashes and memory warnings, especially when users navigate deeply through photo galleries (100+ images). Memory usage grows from 100MB to 800MB before the app is terminated. How would you diagnose memory issues and optimize memory usage? Discuss image caching strategies, ARC, and memory profiling.',
     'Memory problem diagnosis: 800MB for image gallery suggests images not released, memory leak or excessive caching. Diagnosis process: (1) Instruments profiling - use Allocations instrument (track memory over time, identify growth), use Leaks instrument (detect retain cycles), use VM Tracker (virtual memory usage by category). Run instrumented app, navigate gallery, observe memory graph. (2) Memory graph debugger - Xcode Debug Memory Graph, visual representation of object relationships, identify strong reference cycles, filter for leaked objects. (3) Deinit verification - add deinit { print("deallocated") } to view controllers, ensure called when popping navigation stack, if not called = retain cycle. Likely issues identified: (1) Full-resolution images loaded - loading 5MB images for 100px thumbnails, memory explodes quickly. (2) No image cache eviction - images cached to avoid reloading but never evicted, accumulates. (3) Retain cycle with image views or cells - strong references preventing deallocation. (4) Background threads holding images - async downloads retain images after view dismissed. Mitigation strategies: Image loading optimization: (1) Downsampling images - load image at display size, not full resolution. Use ImageIO to downsample while loading: let options = [kCGImageSourceShouldCache: false, kCGImageSourceThumbnailMaxPixelSize: 200]; let thumbnail = CGImageSourceCreateThumbnailAtIndex(...). Reduces 5MB image to 50KB in memory. (2) Lazy loading - load images only when visible (UICollectionView/UITableView cells), cancel loads for off-screen cells, use SDWebImage or Kingfisher libraries (handle caching automatically). (3) Image caching with eviction - use NSCache (automatically evicts under memory pressure): let imageCache = NSCache<NSString, UIImage>(); imageCache.countLimit = 50; imageCache.totalCostLimit = 100 * 1024 * 1024; // 100MB. Manual cache management alternatively: evict based on LRU policy. (4) Progressive image loading - load thumbnail first (instant), load full res if user taps (lazy), cancel if user navigates away. Memory management patterns: (1) Weak references - use [weak self] in closures (async image loads): URLSession.shared.dataTask(...) { [weak self] data, response, error in self?.imageView.image = UIImage(data: data!) } prevents retain cycle if view controller dismissed. (2) Deallocate resources in deinit - cancel ongoing tasks: deinit { imageLoadingTask?.cancel() }. (3) Explicitly nil large objects - imageView.image = nil when view disappears (iOS might not auto-release immediately), especially in didReceiveMemoryWarning. (4) didReceiveMemoryWarning response - implement in view controller: override func didReceiveMemoryWarning() { imageCache.removeAllObjects(); super.didReceiveMemoryWarning() }. Specific fixes for photo gallery: (1) Collection view cell reuse - ensure prepareForReuse clears images: override func prepareForReuse() { imageView.image = nil; imageLoadTask?.cancel() }. (2) Prefetch only adjacent cells - dont prefetch 100 rows ahead, UICollectionViewDataSourcePrefetching for intelligent prefetch. (3) Paging or virtualization - load full-res only for visible page in page viewer, adjacent pages load thumbnails. (4) Background queue for image processing - decompress and resize images off main thread: DispatchQueue.global(qos: .userInitiated).async {... }. ARC (Automatic Reference Counting) considerations: Object deallocated when strong reference count = 0, cycles prevent deallocation (both references keeping each other alive), use weak or unowned to break cycles. Common cycle: view controller → closure → self (view controller), fix with [weak self]. Testing and validation: (1) Memory regression tests - automated tests navigate gallery 10 times, assert memory returns to baseline (<150MB), integrate into CI. (2) Stress testing - load 1000 images sequentially, monitor memory doesn''t exceed threshold, ensure no crashes. (3) Instruments automation - script Instruments runs to detect leaks in CI: xcodebuild test -enableCodeCoverage YES ... | xcpretty. (4) Real device testing - simulators have different memory constraints, test on oldest supported device (lower memory pressure threshold). Expected results: Memory usage: 100MB idle → 250MB during gallery use → returns to ~120MB after dismissal (slight cache overhead acceptable). Zero memory leaks detected by Instruments. No crashes under normal usage. Smooth scrolling (60 fps maintained). Success metrics: Crash-free rate > 99.9%, memory warnings < 1% of sessions, gallery scrolling frame rate > 55fps p95.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 65: Android Development (5 questions)
    (321, 'Explain the Android activity lifecycle. What methods are called during configuration changes like screen rotation?',
     'Activity lifecycle methods (order): onCreate (activity created, setContentView, initialize), onStart (visible but not interactive), onResume (interactive, in foreground), onPause (about to lose focus, save transient state), onStop (no longer visible), onDestroy (activity destroyed). Configuration change (rotation): Current: onPause → onStop → onDestroy, new activity created: onCreate → onStart → onResume. Instance state lost unless saved. Saving state: onSaveInstanceState(Bundle) called before onStop, restore in onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) or onRestoreInstanceState(Bundle). Best practices: save UI state (scroll position, user input), don''t save large data or objects (use ViewModel), handle null savedInstanceState. Preventing recreation: android:configChanges="orientation|screenSize" in manifest, onConfigurationChanged(Configuration) called instead of recreate, must manually handle layout changes (generally not recommended, let system handle). Modern approach: ViewModel survives configuration changes, store UI state and data in ViewModel, activity observes ViewModel, rotation doesn''t lose data. Jetpack Navigation handles back stack correctly. Fragments: own lifecycle (onAttach, onCreate, onCreateView, onViewCreated, onDestroyView, onDetach), nested within Activity lifecycle. Best practice for rotation: ViewModel + LiveData pattern (activity observes LiveData, rotation resubscribes to same ViewModel), save minimal state in onSaveInstanceState (UI state only), avoid blocking onPause/onStop (system kills if slow).',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (322, 'What is the difference between Service, IntentService, and JobScheduler in Android? When would you use each?',
     'Service: runs in background on main thread (not separate thread!), long-running operations without UI, must manually create worker thread for heavy tasks. Types: Started (startService, runs until stopSelf/stopService), Bound (bindService, client-server interaction). Use for: music playback, real-time location tracking (foreground service with notification). Must call startForeground for long-running to avoid being killed. IntentService: handles asynchronous requests (Intents) on worker thread, queues requests serially, automatically stops when queue empty, deprecated in API 30 (use WorkManager or JobIntentService). Use for (legacy): one-off background tasks like upload file, download, database operation. JobScheduler: schedules background jobs with constraints (network available, device charging, idle), system optimizes execution (batching, doze mode compliance), survives app restarts. Use for: periodic sync, upload when WiFi available, background processing that can wait. Modern: WorkManager wraps JobScheduler, BackgroundService, AlarmManager, simpler API, guaranteed execution. Comparison: Service (manual thread management, runs immediately, foreground for long-lived), IntentService (auto worker thread, deprecated), JobScheduler (deferred execution, constraint-based), WorkManager (modern, recommended for most background work). Foreground services: required notification, user-visible, can''t bedismissed, use for media, navigation, fitness tracking. Background execution limits: Android 8+ restricts background services, must use WorkManager or foreground service. Best practice: use WorkManager for deferrable background work (recommended), foreground Service for immediate long-running work user is aware of, JobScheduler directly if need fine-grained control.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (323, 'Explain Android memory leaks. How do you prevent leaks with Activities, Context, and static references?',
     'Memory leak: object no longer needed but still referenced, can''t be garbage collected. Common causes in Android: (1) Static reference to Activity/Context - static variable holds Activity reference after Activity destroyed. Example: static MyClass instance; instance holds Activity context, Activity leaks. Fix: use Application context (getApplicationContext()) for static/singleton, or weak reference. (2) Non-static inner class with long lifetime - Inner class implicitly references outer Activity, example: Handler as inner class, message in queue after Activity finished, Activity leaked. Fix: make Handler static with WeakReference<Activity>, or use Lifecycle-aware components. (3) Anonymous inner classes in async tasks - AsyncTask/Runnable holds Activity reference, task running after Activity destroyed leaks Activity. Fix: static AsyncTask with WeakReference<Activity>, cancel tasks in onDestroy, use Kotlin coroutines with lifecycleScope (auto-cancel). (4) Listeners and callbacks not unregistered - register listener in onCreate, forget to unregister in onDestroy, listener holds Activity reference. Fix: unregister in onPause/onDestroy symmetrically. (5) Context misuse - passing Activity context where ApplicationContext suffices, Activity reference kept longer than needed. Fix: use Application context for long-lived objects (singletons, database), Activity context only for UI-related. Detection: (1) LeakCanary library - automatically detects leaks, shows leak trace, integrate in debug builds. (2) Android Profiler - memory profiler in Android Studio, heap dump analysis, find paths to GC root. (3) Manual verification - rotate screen repeatedly, check memory doesn''t grow, multiple Activity instances = leak. Prevention patterns: (1) WeakReference for Activity in callbacks: class MyClass { private WeakReference<Activity> activityRef; }, access via activityRef.get() (null if destroyed). (2) Lifecycle-aware components - ViewModel, LiveData, WorkManager auto-handle lifecycle. (3) Symmetric register/unregister - onCreate + onDestroy, onStart + onStop, onResume + onPause. (4) Avoid static Activities - never static Activity, Context, View. Best practices: prefer ApplicationContext for singletons, use ViewModel for data surviving configuration changes, test with LeakCanary, cancel async operations in lifecycle callbacks.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (324, 'What is Jetpack Compose? How does it differ from traditional Android View system? Explain state management in Compose.',
     'Jetpack Compose: modern declarative UI toolkit for Android, Kotlin-based, replaces XML layouts and View system. Declarative vs imperative: Imperative (View): manually update UI (setText, setVisibility), manage state explicitly, complex for dynamic UIs. Declarative (Compose): describe UI as function of state, UI auto-updates when state changes, simpler mental model. Example Compose: @Composable fun Greeting(name: String) { Text("Hello $name") }. Key differences: No XML (UI in Kotlin code), less boilerplate (no findViewById, ViewBinding optional), reactive (state changes trigger recomposition), interop (Compose + Views can coexist). Principles: (1) Composable functions - @Composable annotation, pure functions describing UI. (2) Recomposition - Compose re-runs composables when state changes, efficient (skips unchanged composables). (3) Unidirectional data flow - data flows down (parameters), events flow up (callbacks). State management: (1) remember - preserves value across recompositions: val count = remember { mutableStateOf(0) }. (2) mutableStateOf - observable state, triggers recomposition when changed: count.value++. (3) State hoisting - lift state to common ancestor, pass down as parameter, pass callbacks up: @Composable fun Counter(count: Int, onIncrement: () -> Unit). (4) ViewModel integration -ViewModel survives config changes: val viewModel: MyViewModel = viewModel(); val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsState(). Side effects: (1) LaunchedEffect - launch coroutine tied to composition: LaunchedEffect(key) { /* suspend function */ }. (2) DisposableEffect - cleanup resources: DisposableEffect(key) { onDispose { /* cleanup */ } }. (3) derivedStateOf - derived state from other states. Performance: Compose compiler optimizes (skips unchanged composables), stability (stable types marked, fewer recompositions). Best practices: hoist state (stateless composables testable), minimize recomposition (stable params), use remember for expensive computations, separate business logic (ViewModel) from UI (Composables).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),

    
    (325, 'Your Android app shows an ANR (Application Not Responding) dialog when users submit a large form with image uploads. The main thread is blocked for 8-10 seconds during submission. How would you diagnose the ANR and refactor the code to maintain responsiveness? Discuss threading, coroutines, and background execution strategies.',
     'ANR diagnosis: Application Not Responding appears when main thread blocked >5 seconds (input events), >10 seconds (BroadcastReceiver). Symptoms: UI frozen, dialog "App isn''t responding", bad user experience. Diagnosis steps: (1) Review logcat - ANR logs show "main" thread traces, system writes ANR trace to /data/anr/traces.txt, "total blocked time" indicator. (2) StrictMode - detects disk reads/writes, network on main thread: StrictMode.setThreadPolicy(ThreadPolicy.Builder().detectAll().penaltyLog().build()), logs violations during development. (3) Systrace/Perfetto - trace main thread activity, visualize where time spent, identify blocking operations. (4) Code review - look for synchronous network calls, large file I/O, image processing, database operations, JSON parsing on main thread. Root causes identified: (1) Image encoding on main thread - compressing multiple images to JPEG before upload, each 5MB image takes 2-3 seconds, blocks UI. (2) Synchronous network call - form submission using synchronous HTTP POST, waits for server response, network latency blocks thread. (3) Large JSON serialization - converting form data to JSON synchronously, complex nested objects slow. Threading solutions: (1) Traditional approach - HandlerThread/ExecutorService for background work: val executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor(); executor.execute { /* background work */ runOnUiThread { /* update UI */ } }. (2) Kotlin Coroutines (recommended) - structured concurrency:lifecycleScope.launch { val result = withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { /* suspend function, background */ }; /* back on main thread, update UI */ }, automatically lifetime-aware, cancellable. (3) WorkManager for deferrable work - upload in background even if app closed, retry policies, constraint-based (WiFi only). Refactoring strategy: (1) Move image compression off main thread - withContext(Dispatchers.Default) { images.map { compressImage(it) } }, parallel processing if multiple images: images.map { async(Dispatchers.Default) { compress it) } }.awaitAll(). (2) Async network call - use Retrofit with suspend functions: @POST("/submit") suspend fun submitForm(@Body data: FormData): Response, called from coroutine, non-blocking. (3) Progress feedback - show ProgressBar during upload: progressBar visibility = VISIBLE before async work, hide in finally block, keepScreen responsive. (4) Chunked processing - if form has 100 fields, process in batches: fields.chunked(20).forEach { batch -> processBatch(batch); yield() /* cooperative cancellation */ }. (5) debounce user actions - prevent rapid submit clicks: submit button disabled after first click, reenable on completion/error. Coroutine patterns: (1) Launch vs async - launch for fire-and-forget (upload), async when need result, multiple async with awaitAll() for parallel. (2) Dispatchers - Main (UI updates), IO (network, database, files), Default (CPU-intensive computation), custom for specific needs. (3) Exception handling - try/catch within coroutine, CoroutineExceptionHandler for uncaught. (4) Cancellation - check isActive, use yield(), cancelable delay(), cleanup in finally. (5) Sequential vs parallel - sequential: result1 = async1(); result2 = async2(result1); parallel: val (r1, r2) = awaitAll(async1(), async2()). UI responsiveness patterns: (1) Optimistic UI update - update UI immediately (assume success), revert on failure, perceived performance boost. (2) Background service for upload - offload to Service/WorkManager, app can be closed, notification shows progress. (3) Pagination form - split large form into steps, submit incrementally, avoid single large blocking operation. (4) Local draft save - save form locally first (instant), sync to server background, even if crash, draft safe. Testing ANR resolution: (1) StrictMode in tests - fails test if main thread violation detected. (2) Espresso with idling resources - wait for async operations, test UI responsive during operation. (3) UI Automator stress test - simulate rapid user interaction, ensure no ANRs. (4) Firebase Performance Monitoring - track slow/frozen frames in production, percentile analysis (p95, p99). Validation metrics: Main thread blocked time <100ms (StrictMode threshold), form submission perceived instant (progress shown immediately), actual upload completes background (2-5 seconds acceptable with feedback), zero ANRs in production (Firebase Crashlytics). Architecture considerations: move to MVVM pattern - ViewModel handles business logic with coroutines, Activity observes LiveData/StateFlow, separation of concerns. Repository layer handles network/database on appropriate dispatchers. Result: Submit button click → immediately show progress → background coroutine compresses images and uploads → UI remains responsive (user can even go back) → completion callback updates UI (success/error). ANRs eliminated, user experience improved significantly.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 66: React Native (5 questions)
    (326, 'What is the bridge in React Native? How does JavaScript communicate with native code?',
     'Bridge: communication layer between JavaScript and native (iOS/Android) code, asynchronous message passing. Architecture: Three threads: (1) JavaScript thread - runs React code, business logic. (2) Native thread - UI rendering, native modules. (3) Shadow thread - layout calculations (Yoga layout engine). Communication flow: JS calls native module → message serialized to JSON → sent across bridge → native code executes → result serialized → sent back to JS → callback executed. Example: TouchableOpacity pressed → JS detects → sends message to native → native updates UI → sends event back to JS. Bridge limitations: (1) Asynchronous - can''t return values directly, use callbacks/promises. (2) JSON serialization overhead - large data expensive, avoid frequent large payloads. (3) Batching - messages batched to reduce overhead, slight delay. Native modules: expose native functionality to JS, example: create native module for Bluetooth: @ReactMethod public void scan(Callback callback), register module, JS imports: import { NativeModules } from "react-native"; NativeModules.BluetoothModule.scan(callback). New architecture (JSI - JavaScript Interface): direct communication without bridge, synchronous calls possible, shared memory, faster. Turbo Modules: lazy-loaded native modules, better startup performance. Fabric: new rendering system, shadow thread integrated with native, more responsive. Best practices with bridge: minimize bridge traffic (batch updates, avoid frequent calls), optimize serialization (don''t send large objects, use native processing), use native modules for performance-critical (camera, animations, heavy computation), direct manipulation for animations (useNativeDriver: true, runs on native thread without bridge). Performance: bridge can become bottleneck (high-frequency updates), migrate to JSI for critical paths, profile with Systrace/React DevTools.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (327, 'Explain React Native FlatList optimization. How do you prevent performance issues with large lists?',
     'FlatList: performant list component, renders only visible items (windowing/virtualization). Props for optimization: (1) keyExtractor - unique key for each item: keyExtractor={(item) => item.id}, prevents re-renders when data reorders. (2) getItemLayout - if items fixed height, provide dimensions: getItemLayout={(data, index) => ({length: ITEM_HEIGHT, offset: ITEM_HEIGHT * index, index})}, skips measurement, faster scrolling. (3) windowSize - number of screens to render (default 21 - 10 above, 10 below, 1 current), reduce to 5 for memory-constrained: windowSize={5}. (4) maxToRenderPerBatch - items rendered per batch (default 10), lower for complex items. (5) updateCellsBatchingPeriod - delay between batches (ms, default 50), increase for smoother scroll. (6) removeClippedSubviews - unmount off-screen items (Android), saves memory: removeClippedSubviews={true}, can cause blank items if buggy. (7) initialNumToRender - items rendered initially (default 10), enough to fill screen. Common performance issues: (1) Complex renderItem - heavy components slow down, optimize: use React.memo (avoid re-renders if props unchanged), extract to separate component, minimize inline functions/objects. (2) Large data arrays - 10,000+ items slow, solutions: pagination (load more on scroll), search/filter server-side, section lists (SectionList). (3) Images in list - unoptimized images (large, not cached), use FastImage library (better caching, priority loading), provide image dimensions, lazy load. (4) Inline functions - created every render, breaks shouldComponentUpdate: Bad: renderItem={({item}) => <Row onPress={() => handlePress(item)} />}; Good: renderItem renderRow (defined outside, reference passed). (5) Deep re-renders - entire list re-renders on unrelated state change, use context carefully, separate list state from other state. Best practices: (1) PureComponent/React.memo for list items - prevent unnecessary re-renders. (2) getItemLayout for fixed-size items - massive scroll performance boost. (3) Use key, not index - stable keys critical for React reconciliation. (4) Optimize images - resize server-side, use appropriate formats, cache aggressively. (5) Monitor performance - use React Native performance monitor (FPS, JS thread usage), profile with Systrace. (6) Consider alternatives - RecyclerListView (better performance for complex lists), Flashlist (Shopify, faster FlatList replacement). Advanced: virtualization window tuning (specific windowSize for your items), on-demand image loading (load image when item rendered, cancel when unmounted), debounced search (avoid re-filtering on every keystroke).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (328, 'How do you handle navigation in React Native? Compare React Navigation and React Native Navigation.',
     'React Navigation: JavaScript-based, most popular, official recommendation, pure JS solution. Pros: cross-platform (iOS, Android, Web), easy integration, extensive docs, customizable, large ecosystem (drawer, tabs, stack). Types: Stack (push/pop), Tab (bottom/top tabs), Drawer (side menu), can nest. Basic usage: const Stack = createNativeStackNavigator(); <Stack.Navigator><Stack.Screen name="Home" component={HomeScreen} /></Stack.Navigator>; navigation prop: navigation.navigate("Details", { itemId: 42 }); params accessed: route.params.itemId. Features: deep linking, state persistence, screen options (headerTitle, headerRight), gestures (swipe back), transitions. React Native Navigation (Wix): native navigation, iOS UINavigationController, Android FragmentManager. Pros: native performance (smoother), native look/feel, better for complex apps. Cons: more setup, platform-specific bugs, smaller community. Comparison: Performance - React Navigation (JS, slight lag complex), Native Navigation (native, better, especially large stacks). Developer experience - React Navigation (easier, better DX), Native Navigation (more config). Cross-platform - React Navigation (Web support), Native Navigation (mobile only). Community - React Navigation (larger, more resources). When to choose: React Navigation for: most apps (good enough performance), Web compatibility needed, faster development, simpler setup. Native Navigation for: performance-critical (complex animations, large stacks), need native feel (iOS/Android platform conventions), integrating with heavily native app. Modern alternatives: React Navigation 6+ uses native stack by default (@react-navigation/native-stack), close to native performance, best of both. Navigation state management: centralized ref: const navigationRef = useNavigationContainerRef(); navigate outside components: navigationRef.navigate("Home"). Deep linking: Linking config, URL schemes, universal links. Best practices: typed routes (TypeScript), centralize routes (constants file), avoid passing large data in params (use context/global state, pass ID only), handle back button (Android), test navigation flows (integration tests).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (329, 'What are the differences between React Native and developing separate native apps? What are the trade-offs?',
     'React Native advantages: (1) Code sharing - single codebase for iOS/Android (70-90% shared), faster development, fewer developers needed. (2) Faster iterations - hot reload, Expo updates (over-the-air), no app store approval for JS changes. (3) Developer pool - hire JavaScript developers (larger pool), existing web developers transition easily. (4) Cross-platform consistency - shared business logic, similar UX across platforms, easier maintenance. (5) Cost - reduced development time, smaller team. Native advantages: (1) Performance - direct native code, no bridge overhead, better for graphics-intensive (games, complex animations). (2) Platform features - immediate access to new APIs (iOS 17 features day one), no waiting for RN support. (3) Platform conventions - easier to follow iOS Human Interface Guidelines, Material Design precisely, native feel. (4) Tooling - Xcode, Android Studio mature, better debugging, profiling. (5) Ecosystem - all native libraries available immediately, no compatibility issues. Trade-offs: Development speed - RN faster (shared code), Native slower (two codebases) but more control. Performance - RN good for most apps (business, social, e-commerce), Native better for high-performance (games, video editing, AR). UI/UX - RN can achieve native look but requires effort, Native natural platform feel, easier pixel-perfect designs. Third-party libs - RN limited (need native modules or bridge), Native full access. Team skills - RN needs JS +some native (bridging), Native needs iOS + Android separate teams. Maintenance - RN single codebase easier, Native two codebases but cleaner separation. When React Native excels: MVP/startup (speed to market), content apps (social, news, e-commerce), existing web codebase (reuse logic), limited budget/team, frequent updates. When Native excels: performance-critical apps (games, video/photo editing), heavy platform integration (HealthKit, ARKit), large established company (dedicated native teams), app defining brand (needs perfect platform UX). Hybrid approach: React Native with native modules for critical paths, example: Airbnb (tried RN, moved back to native due to complexity), Facebook (uses RN for many features, native for core), Microsoft (heavily invested in RN). Best practice: evaluate per app requirements (performance, budget, timeline, team skills), prototype in RN for speed, drop to native if performance insufficient, modern RN (New Architecture) narrows performance gap significantly.',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (330, 'Your React Native app''s JavaScript bundle size has grown to 8MB, causing slow initial load times (10+ seconds on 3G networks). Users also complaint about occasional crashes on older Android devices (4GB RAM). How would you optimize bundle size, improve load times, and reduce memory footprint? Discuss code splitting, lazy loading, and performance profiling.',
     'Problem analysis: 8MB bundle = slow download (10s on 3G), parse/execute slow (older devices), memory pressure (large bundle in memory), crashes on low-memory devices. Diagnosis steps: (1) Bundle analysis - use react-native-bundle-visualizer or source-map-explorer: npx react-native-bundle-visualizer, identifies large dependencies, duplicate packages, unused code. (2) Metro bundler analysis - inspect metro.config.js, check for large assets, inline base64. (3) Memory profiling - React DevTools Profiler, Android Studio Memory Profiler, identify memory leaks, large object allocations. (4) Network analysis - Charles Proxy or Chrome DevTools, measure actual download time, bundle vs assets split. Likely issues identified: (1) Large dependencies - moment.js (67KB), lodash (entire library 70KB), react-native-vector-icons (all icons), unused polyfills. (2) Development code in production - __DEV__ checks, console.logs, debugging tools. (3) Large images in bundle - PNG images inlined, should be assets. (4) No code splitting - entire app in single bundle, loaded upfront. Bundle size optimization: (1) Tree shaking - ensure imports named: import { debounce } from "lodash" → import debounce from "lodash/debounce", saves 60KB+. (2) Replace large libraries - moment.js (67KB) → date-fns (2KB per function) or day.js (2KB), lodash (70KB) → individual functions or native methods, react-native-vector-icons → selective icon sets. (3) Remove unused dependencies - audit package.json, npx depcheck finds unused, remove dead code. (4) ProGuard/R8 - Android minification, shrinks native code, removes unused classes. (5) Hermes engine - Android JS engine, smaller bytecode, faster startup, enable in android/app/build.gradle: project.ext.react = [enableHermes: true], iOS Hermes available React Native 0.70+. (6) Metro RAM bundles - indexed format, faster startup Android: bundleCommand: "ram-bundle". (7) Strip console.logs in production - babel plugin transform-remove-console removes prod builds. Code splitting strategies: (1) Lazy loading screens - React.lazy + Suspense (experimental RN support), load screens on navigation: const SettingsScreen = React.lazy(() => import("./SettingsScreen")), reduces initial bundle (load on demand). (2) Dynamic imports - await import("./HeavyModule") when needed, example: load chart library when user opens analytics (not upfront). (3) Bundle splitting (advanced) - separate vendor bundle from app code, common chunks across screens, requires custom Metro config or Haul bundler. ( 4) Feature flags - disable features for low-tier devices, conditional imports: if (Platform.OS === "ios") { import iOSFeature }. Asset optimization: (1) Image compression - use WebP (30% smaller than JPEG), compress with tools like TinyPNG, provide multiple resolutions (@2x, @3x). (2) External image loading - don''t bundle large images, load from CDN, use FastImage with caching. (3) Font subsetting - include only needed glyphs, custom fonts can be large. (4) remove unused assets - audit images, unused icons, dead assets. Memory footprint reduction: (1) Lazy component mounting - render expensive components only when needed, unmount when navigated away. (2) FlatList optimization - windowSize reduction, removeClippedSubviews, prevents all items in memory. (3) Image memory management - clear ImageCache on memory warning: ImageCache.clear(), use lower resolution on low-memory devices. (4) Avoid memory leaks - clear timers/listeners on unmount, use weak Maps for caches, profile with Heap snapshots. (5) Navigation stack limits - limit stack depth (pop old screens), use replace navigation instead of push for flows. (6) Release builds testing - debug builds have overhead, test memory on release builds. Platform-specific optimizations: Android - (1) Enable Hermes - reduces bundle size 50%, faster startup, better memory. (2) Use APK splits - separate APKs per ABI (arm64, x86), users download only their architecture: splits: { abi: true }. (3) Enable multidex - if methods exceed 64K. (4) ProGuard enabled in release. iOS - (1) Bitcode enabled (Xcode optimization). (2) Dead code stripping in Xcode build settings. (3) Xcode optimization level -Os (optimize for size). Load time improvement: (1) Splash screen optimization - native splash screen (instant), placeholder UI while bundle loads, perceived performance. (2) Incremental loading - show critical UI first (home screen), lazy load rest (profile, settings). (3) Cache bundlechunks - CodePush or Expo Updates, users download updates incrementally, faster subsequent loads. (4) Preload critical data - fetch initial data while bundle parsing, parallel loading. (5) Optimize JS execution - minimize heavy computations at startup, defer analytics initialization, lazy initialize singletons. (6) inline requires - Metro inline require optimization, modules loaded when used: asyncRequire: true in metro.config. Monitoring and validation: (1) Bundle size CI check - fail build if bundle exceeds threshold: if [ $( stat -f%z main.jsbundle) -gt 5000000 ]; then exit 1; fi. (2) Performance monitoring - Firebase Performance, monitor app start time, track percentiles (p50, p95, p99). (3) Device testing - test on low-end devices (Android 4GB RAM, old iPhone), simulate slow networks (Chrome DevTools throttling). (4) Track metrics - bundle size over time (graph in CI), start time regression detection, crash-free rate by device tier. Expected results: Bundle size 8MB → 3-4MB (50% reduction from tree shaking, library replacement, Hermes), load time 10s → 3-4s on 3G (smaller bundle + splash optimization), memory usage stable (no growth from leaks), crashes on 4GB devices eliminated (proper memory management), smooth user experience (perceived as instant with splash). Success metrics: p95 app start time <5s on 3G, bundle size <4MB, zero memory-related crashes, 99.5%+ crash-free rate on all devices.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),


    -- Topic 67: Flutter (5 questions)
    (331, 'What is the difference between StatefulWidget and StatelessWidget in Flutter?',
     'StatelessWidget: immutable widget, UI doesn''t change after built, rebuild only when parent changes. Example: Icon, Text with fixed content. Build method called when parent rebuilds or initial render. Use for: static content, UI depending only on configuration (constructor params), pure functions of inputs. Implementation: class MyWidget extends StatelessWidget { @override Widget build(BuildContext context) { return Text("Static"); } }. StatefulWidget: mutable state, can change over time, triggers rebuilds when setState called. Two classes: widget (configuration, immutable) State (mutable state, lives across rebuilds). Example: Checkbox, TextField, animated widgets. Lifecycle: createState (widget creates state object once), initState (state initializes), build (creates widget tree), setState (marks dirty, triggers rebuild), dispose (cleanup). Use for: interactive UI (forms, buttons), data changes over time (API responses, animations), depends on user input. Implementation: class Counter extends StatefulWidget { @override _CounterState createState() => _CounterState(); } class _CounterState extends State<Counter> { int count = 0; void increment() { setState(() { count++; }); } @override Widget build(BuildContext context) { return Text("$count"); } }. Key differences: StatelessWidget rebuilds from parent, StatefulWidget rebuilds internally via setState, StatefulWidget has State object persisted across rebuilds (widget recreated, state reused). StatelessWidget more performant (no state management overhead). Best practices: prefer StatelessWidget when possible (easier to reason, better performance), use const constructors (Flutter optimization, reuses widgets), lift state up (common ancestor manages state, children stateless), use state management solutions for complex state (Provider, Riverpod, Bloc), avoid deep widget trees (extract to smaller widgets).',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (332, 'Explain Flutter''s declarative UI approach. How does it differ from imperative UI frameworks?',
     'Declarative UI: describe what UI should look like for given state, framework handles updates. Flutter: build method returns widget tree representing current state, when state changes, rebuild widget tree, Flutter diffs and updates efficiently. Example: build() { return isLoading ? CircularProgressIndicator() : Text(data); }, state change (isLoading = false) → rebuild → Flutter updates UI. Imperative UI: manually describe how to change UI step-by-step. Traditional Android/iOS: myTextView.setText("new text"); progressBar.setVisibility(GONE); etc., must track current state and mutations. Comparison benefits declarative: (1) Simpler mental model - UI = f(state), always know what UI looks like for state, no need to track mutations. (2) Easier debugging - widget tree inspection, state snapshot shows exact UI, reproducible. (3) Better composition - small widgets composed into complex UIs, reusable components. (4) Less bugs - no invalid states (forgot to hide loading), state and UI always synced. (5) Testable - pure functions easy to test, mock state, verify widget tree. Drawbacks: (1) Performance concerns - rebuild entire tree expensive, Flutter optimizes (widget reuse, const, RenderObject layer). (2) Learning curve - different paradigm for imperative developers. Flutter architecture: three trees: (1) Widget tree - lightweight configuration, rebuilt frequently, immutable. (2) Element tree - manages lifespan, holds state, updated incrementally. (3) RenderObject tree - actual layout/paint, expensive, updated only when necessary. Performance optimization: (1) const constructors - const Text("Hello") marked as compile-time constant, reused across rebuilds, huge performance gain. (2) Keys - preserve widget state when order changes, GlobalKey for specific widget access. (3) Builder pattern - rebuilds only subtree: StatefulBuilder, StreamBuilder, FutureBuilder. (4) shouldrebuild - CustomScrollView, RepaintBoundary prevent unnecessary repaints. React comparison: similar declarative model (JSX), Flutter compiles to native (faster than React Native bridge), Flutter widgets vs React components (analogous), setState vs useState (similar state triggers). Best practices: think in widgets (composition over inheritance), pure build methods (no side effects), use const aggressively (free performance), separate business logic from UI (BLoC, ViewModel), embrace rebuilds (Flutter optimizes well, don''t overthink).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (333, 'What are Flutter providers and state management? Compare Provider, Riverpod, and Bloc patterns.',
     'State management: how to share/manage state across widget tree, avoid prop drilling, separate business logic from UI. Options: (1) setState - local widget state, simple, doesn''t scale. (2) InheritedWidget - low-level state propagation down tree, manual, verbose. (3) Provider - wrapper around InheritedWidget, most popular, simple API. (4) Riverpod - improved Provider, compile-safe, no BuildContext. (5) Bloc - event-driven, business logic component pattern, complex but powerful. (6) Others: GetX, MobX, Redux. Provider pattern: ChangeNotifier (observable), Provider widget provides value, Consumer rebuilds on change. Example: class Counter extends ChangeNotifier { int _count = 0; int get count => _count; void increment() { _count++; notifyListeners(); } }. Provide: ChangeNotifierProvider(create: (_) => Counter(), child: MyApp()). Consume: Consumer<Counter>(builder: (context, counter, child) => Text("${counter.count}")). Pros: simple, official recommendation, integrates well, small learning curve. Cons: requires BuildContext, runtime errors if provider not found, global mutable state. Riverpod pattern: evolution of Provider, compile-time safety, no BuildContext needed, testable providers. Providers defined globally: final counterProvider = StateNotifierProvider<Counter, int>((ref) => Counter()). Consume: Consumer(builder: (context, ref, child) { final count = ref.watch(counterProvider); return Text("$count"); }). Pros: compile-safe (no missing provider errors), easier testing, scoped providers, auto-dispose. Cons: more boilerplate than Provider, newer (smaller community). Bloc pattern: Business Logic Component pattern, UI sends events, Bloc processes (business logic), emits states, UI listens and rebuilds. Three components: Events (user actions), States (UI states), Bloc (transformation events → states via streams). Example: Events: sealed class CounterEvent { Increment, Decrement }. States: class CounterState { final int count; }. Bloc: class CounterBloc extends Bloc<CounterEvent, CounterState> { on<Increment>((event, emit) => emit(CounterState(count: state.count + 1))); }. UI: BlocBuilder<CounterBloc, CounterState>(builder: (context, state) => Text("${state.count}")). Pros: clear separation (business logic independent), testable (mock events, verify states), scalable (complex apps), time-travel debugging, event logging. Cons: boilerplate (lots of files), learning curve, overkill for simple apps. Comparison: Simple apps - Provider (easy start, minimal setup). Medium apps - Riverpod (compile safety worth it, scales well). Complex/enterprise - Bloc (architecture worth boilerplate, maintainability). Team preference - all viable, consistency matters more than choice. When to choose: Provider if: small-medium app, team familiar, rapid development. Riverpod if: want compile safety, testing priority, greenfield project. Bloc if: large app, clear architecture needed, event sourcing valuable, complex business logic. Best practices: separate business logic from UI (all patterns), test state changes (unit test providers/blocs), minimize providers (don''t create provider for every piece of state), use selectors (rebuild only when relevant state changes), immutable state (easier debugging, prevents bugs).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),

    (334, 'How does Flutter achieve 60fps performance? Explain the rendering pipeline and frame budget.',
     'Frame budget: 60fps = 16.67ms per frame (1000ms / 60), Flutter must complete build + layout + paint + rasterize within budget, exceeding causes jank (dropped frames). Rendering pipeline: (1) Build phase - widget.build() called, creates widget tree (configuration), lightweight, const widgets reused. (2) Layout phase - RenderObject tree, each render object calculates size/position, constraints flow down (parent constraints), sizes flow up (child sizes), O(n) single-pass. (3) Paint phase - RenderObjects paint themselves to layers (Skia commands), compositing, RepaintBoundaries create new layers (isolate repaints). (4) Rasterization phase - Skia converts paint commands to GPU instructions (separate thread!), GPU draws pixels. (5) Composition - engine combines layers, sends to screen. Key insight: UI thread (Dart) builds/layouts/paints to layers, GPU thread rasterizes in parallel, keeps both threads <16ms for 60fps. Performance optimizations: (1) const constructors - widget not rebuilt, reused from previous frame, massive savings (const Text vs Text). (2) Keys - preserve element state, avoid unnecessary rebuilds when list reorders, GlobalKey, ValueKey, ObjectKey. (3) RepaintBoundary - isolates widget repaints, expensive widget wrapped, only that portion repaints (not entire tree), example: ListView items. (4) Opacity avoidance - Opacity widget expensive (repaints children), prefer AnimatedOpacity or directly set alpha on Colors. (5) ClipRRect alternatives - clipping forces layer (expensive), prefer decoration (faster). (6) Build method purity - avoid heavy computation in build (move to initState or memoize), no network calls or state mutations. (7) ListView.builder - lazy loading, renders only visible items, compared to ListView (renders all children). (8) Image caching - flutter caches decoded images, provide cacheWidth/cacheHeight to reduce memory. Measuring performance: (1) Flutter DevTools performance tab - flame chart shows frame times, identify slow frames (>16ms), drill into build/layout/paint phases. (2) Performance overlay - FPS counter, shows GPU/UI thread times: flutter run --profile, green bars good, red bad. (3) Timeline events - detailed breakdown of frame construction. (4) Rendering layers - Toggle debugRepaintRainbowEnabled (shows repainting regions), debugPaintLayerBordersEnabled (shows layers). Common jank causes: (1) Heavy build - complex widget tree, many widgets built each frame, solution: memoization, extract subtrees. (2) Synchronous I/O - reading files, network in build, blocks UI thread, solution: FutureBuilder, async. (3) Large images - full-res 5MB images in memory, layout/rasterize expensive, solution: resize images, cacheWidth. (4) Shader compilation - first frame shows animation, shader compiled, janks (shader warmup issue), solution: warmup shaders or use SkSL. (5) Unbounded layout - ListView in Column without height (infinite), solution: Expanded, SizedBox with height. Best practices: (1) Use Profile mode for performance testing (debug mode slow, release mode optimized but no DevTools, profile mode balanced). (2) Target 60fps but allow headroom (~14ms per frame leaves buffer). (3) Optimize for 90/120Hz displays (flagship phones), 11ms/8ms budgets. (4) Debounce rapid rebuilds - setState during animation = rebuild every frame (60 times/second), avoid if possible. (5) Prefer GPU over CPU - use Transform (GPU accelerated) not widget repositioning, animations with GPU layers. (6) Profile on real devices - emulators not representative, test low-end Android (performance floor). Advanced: Flutter can hit 120fps (8.3ms budget), requires careful optimization (minimal rebuilds, GPU-accelerated animations), benchmark consistently (automated performance tests in CI).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (335, 'Your Flutter app experiences severe frame drops (10-15fps) when scrolling through a feed with images, complex cards, and animations. Users report the app feels laggy and unresponsive. How would you diagnose the performance issues and optimize rendering? Discuss Flutter DevTools, rendering pipeline, and widget optimization strategies.',
     'Performance problem: 60fps target (16.67ms/frame), 10-15fps = 66-100ms/frame (4-6x budget), indicates severe bottleneck in build/layout/paint/rasterize phases. Systematic diagnosis: (1) Enable performance overlay - run profile build: flutter run --profile, observe FPS counter, check which thread limiting (UI thread = green bar, GPU thread = red bar), UI thread issues = Dart code slow (build/layout), GPU issues = rasterization expensive (complex graphics). (2) Flutter DevTools timeline - open DevTools, record scrolling session, examine flame chart (horizontal bars = time spent), identify long frames (red indicators), drill into frame breakdown (build, layout, paint phases), look for repeated expensive operations per frame. (3) Layer visualization - enable debugPaintLayerBordersEnabled = true, shows compositing layers, too many layers = excessive compositing overhead, look for unnecessary RepaintBoundaries. (4) Repaint rainbow - debugRepaintRainbowEnabled = true, flashing colors show repainting regions, excessive repainting = problem (should only repaint changing areas), entire screen flashing = rebuilding everything (bad). (5) Widget rebuild tracking - Add print statements in build methods temporarily, count rebuilds per scroll, ideally only visible items rebuild, all rebuilding = state management issue. Likely root causes identified: (1) ListView inefficiencies - using ListView constructor (builds all children upfront) instead of ListView.builder (lazy), not using itemExtent or prototypeItem (forces layout of all items). (2) Heavy widget builds - complex card widget rebuilds frequently, inline computations in build (formatting, calculations every frame), large widget trees (deep nesting). (3) Image issues - full-resolution images loaded (5MB each), no caching or resizing, decoding images every frame, memory pressure. (4) Animation overhead - simultaneous animations on multiple cards, animating properties that require relayout (size, position), Opacity widgets (force repaints). (5) State management issues - entire ListView wrapped in Consumer/Selector, unrelated state changes trigger full rebuild, lack of const constructors (widgets recreated every build). Optimization strategies: ListView optimization: (1) Use ListView.builder - only builds visible items: ListView.builder(itemCount: items.length, itemBuilder: (context, index) => buildCard(items[index])), virtualization handles rest. (2) Provide itemExtent - if items fixed height: itemExtent: 120, skips expensive layout measurements, massive performance boost. (3) Use prototypeItem - if items similar height but variable: prototypeItem: CardWidget(items[0]), Flutter measures once, applies to all. (4) Cache extent tuning - cacheExtent: 200 controls off-screen rendering buffer, lower = less memory/build, higher = smoother but more expensive. (5) Add RepaintBoundary to items - wraps each card: RepaintBoundary(child: CardWidget()), isolates repaints (one card animates doesn''t repaint others), but don''t overuse (too many layers expensive). Widget build optimization: (1) Extract to StatelessWidget - separate card into own widget class, use const constructor where possible: const CardHeader(), widget reused across frames. (2) Use const liberally - any widget that doesn''t change: const Divider(), const SizedBox(height: 8), compile-time constants never rebuilt. (3) Memoize expensive computations - don''t format dates in build: final formattedDate = useMemoized(() => DateFormat().format(date), [date]), recomputes only when dependency changes. (4) Minimize widget depth - flatten widget tree where possible, each level = overhead, use RichText instead of nested Text widgets. (5) Keys for list items - stable keys prevent unnecessary rebuilds when list reorders: key: ValueKey(item.id), Flutter reuses widgets correctly. Image optimization: (1) Resize images appropriately - don''t load 4000x3000 for 200x200 display, use cacheWidth/cacheHeight: Image.network(url, cacheWidth: 400), Flutter resizes during decode (saves memory). (2) Precache images - loading image during scroll = jank, precache before display: precacheImage(NetworkImage(url), context) in initState or didChangeDependencies. (3) Use image caching library - CachedNetworkImage package, disk + memory cache, placeholder while loading, automatic retry: CachedNetworkImage(imageUrl: url, placeholder: (context, url) => Skeleton(), errorWidget: ErrorIcon()). (4) Image format optimization - use WebP (smaller), progressive JPEG (loads gradually), compress server-side before delivering. (5) Reduce memory footprint - Image.network vs FileImage vs MemoryImage, memory images fastest but RAM-intensive, balance based on constraints. Animation optimization: (1) Avoid animating expensive properties - size/position triggers relayout (expensive), opacity/color/transform cheaper, Transform (GPU-accelerated) vs Container repositioning (CPU). (2) Implicit animations - AnimatedOpacity, AnimatedContainer handle efficiently, compared to manual setState + rebuild. (3) Stagger animations - don''t animate 20 cards simultaneously, stagger delays (creates wave effect, spreads load). (4) Use AnimationController judiciously - dispose properly: @override dispose() { _controller.dispose(); super.dispose(); }, leaked controllers keep ticking (waste CPU). State management optimization: (1) Fine-grained selectors - rebuild only affected widgets: Selector<Model, String>(selector: (_, model) => model.specificField, builder: (_, field, __) => Text(field)), compared to Consumer (rebuilds on any model change). (2) Const widgets in builders - Consumer<Model>(builder: (context, model, child) => Column(children: [const Header(), DataWidget(model.data), child!]), child: const Footer()), child param passed through (not rebuilt). (3) Separate static widgets - extract non-changing parts outside builder, reduces rebuild scope. (4) Use keys to preserve state - prevents widget recreation, preserves animations/scroll positions. GPU thread optimization: (1) Reduce layer count - merge layers where possible, don''t overuse Opacity, ClipRRect, BackdropFilter (create layers). (2) Simplify graphics - reduce custom painting complexity, avoid saveLayer calls (expensive), use simpler shapes. (3) Shader warm-up - compile shaders ahead: build/post-build step or ShaderWarmUp widget, prevents first-frame jank. Advanced techniques: (1) Automated performance tests - integration tests that assert frame metrics: await tester.pumpWidget(app); await tester.drag(find.byType(ListView), Offset(0, -500)); FrameTimingSummarizer().summarize(binding.frameTimings), fails if p90 > threshold. (2) Custom render objects - for ultra-performance-critical widgets, skip widget/element layers, create RenderObject directly, complex but ultimate control. (3) Isolates for computation - heavy processing (image filters, data transforms) off main thread: compute(expensiveFunction, data), returns Future, doesn''t block UI. (4) Profile guided optimization - use Timeline events, optimize hottest paths first (80/20 rule), measure before/after. Testing and validation: (1) Profile mode testing - always test in --profile (representative), debug mode 10x slower (misleading), release mode no DevTools (can''t diagnose). (2) Real device spectrum - test on low-end device (defines performance floor), if smooth on cheap Android, great everywhere, flagship devices hide problems. (3) Network conditions - throttle network (slow 3G), image loading delays apparent, ensure loading states don''t cause jank. (4) Automated checks - CI pipeline performance tests: flutter drive --target=test_driver/perf_test.dart --profile, assert frame times acceptable, regression detection. Expected results post-optimization: FPS: 10-15fps → 55-60fps sustained (maybe 50fps on absolute low-end, acceptable), frame time: 66-100ms → 14-16ms (within budget), DevTools timeline: even frame bars (no red spikes), clean rendering (only visible cards repaint), smooth user experience: 60fps feels fluid, zero perceived lag. Metrics to track: Average FPS over 30s scroll session, Percentage of dropped frames <5%, p99 frame time <20ms, memory usage stable (no growth over time indicating leaks). Success = users report responsiveness restored, scrolling buttery smooth.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 68: Mobile Architecture (5 questions)
    (336, 'What is the MVC pattern in mobile development? How does it compare to MVVM and MVP?',
     'MVC (Model-View-Controller): traditional pattern, separates concerns. Model (data/business logic), View (UI), Controller (mediates, handles input). Flow: User interacts with View → Controller updates Model → Model notifies View → View updates. Mobile issues: Controllers become massive (Massive View Controller problem in iOS), tight coupling View-Controller, hard to test (Controller depends on View). MVP (Model-View-Presenter): evolution of MVC for testability. Model (data), View (UI interface), Presenter (business logic, updates View through interface). Flow: View delegates to Presenter → Presenter updates Model → Presenter tells View what to display. Benefits: Presenter testable (View is interface, easily mocked), clear separation, View passive (dumb). Implementation: protocol ViewProtocol { func showLoading(); func displayData(String) }; class Presenter { weak var view: ViewProtocol? }; view calls presenter.loadData(), presenter calls view.showLoading(). Use in Android commonly. MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel): data binding focused, popularized by Microsoft. Model (data), View (UI), ViewModel (exposes Model data, commands for View). Flow: View binds to ViewModel properties → ViewModel property changes → View auto-updates (observe). Benefits: declarative (less boilerplate), testable (ViewModel independent), reactive (LiveData, RxJava, Combine). Implementation iOS: class ViewModel: ObservableObject { @Published var data: String }, SwiftUI View observes: @StateObject var viewModel = ViewModel(); Text(viewModel.data). Android: ViewModel + LiveData, View observes: viewModel.data.observe(this) { updateUI(it) }. Comparison: Testing - MVC (hard, coupled), MVP (easy, interface mocking), MVVM (easy, bindings testable). Boilerplate - MVC (low), MVP (medium, interfaces), MVVM (low with binding frameworks). Platform fit - MVC (web traditional), MVP (Android pre-Jetpack), MVVM (modern mobile, SwiftUI, Jetpack Compose). Data flow - MVC (bidirectional, complex), MVP (clear delegation), MVVM (reactive, observables). When to choose: MVC - simple apps (CRUD), legacy codebases. MVP - Android Views (XML), need strict separation, large teams (clear contracts). MVVM - modern (SwiftUI, Jetpack Compose), reactive data (LiveData, Combine), rapid UI development. Best practices: whichever chosen, stick consistently, thin controllers/presenters/viewmodels (business logic in Model/domain layer), test business logic (independent of UI framework), use dependency injection (loose coupling).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),

    
    (337, 'What is Clean Architecture for mobile apps? Explain the dependency rule and layers.',
     'Clean Architecture: Robert C. Martin (Uncle Bob) architecture, separates concerns in concentric circles, dependencies point inward (outer layers depend on inner, never reverse). Layers (outside to inside): (1) Frameworks & Drivers (outermost) - UI (SwiftUI, Android Views), database (Room, Core Data), network (Retrofit, Alamofire), external dependencies, framework-specific code. (2) Interface Adapters - presenters, view models, controllers, repositories, data mappers (DTO to domain entities), converts data between use case format and external format. (3) Use Cases / Interactors - application business logic, specific to app (FetchUserProfile, ProcessPayment), orchestrates data flow, platform-independent. (4) Entities (innermost) - enterprise business logic, pure objects representing core business, no dependencies on outer layers (no UIKit, no Android SDK). Dependency Rule: inner layers know nothing about outer layers, source code dependencies point inward only, Entities don't import Use Cases, Use Cases don't import ViewModels, achieved via Dependency Inversion (interfaces). Example mobile structure: Entities - User, Order (plain Kotlin/Swift classes). Use Cases - GetUserUseCase (fetches from repository interface). Repository Interface - UserRepository protocol (defined in inner layer). Repository Implementation - UserRepositoryImpl (outer layer, uses network client). ViewModel - calls use case, prepares data for view. View - displays data from ViewModel. Benefits: (1) Testability - inner layers pure logic, easily unit tested without mocks, use cases test business logic without UI/database. (2) Independence - business logic doesn''t depend on framework (can switch UIKit to SwiftUI, change database without touching use cases). (3) Flexibility - outer layers changeable (new API client, different UI), core stable. Challenges: (1) Boilerplate - many layers, interfaces, mappers (DTO → Entity → ViewModel). (2) Overkill for simple apps - overhead not justified for CRUD apps. (3) Learning curve - team training required. Mobile adaptation: Often simplified to three layers: Domain (entities + use cases), Data (repositories + data sources), Presentation (ViewModels + Views). Best practices: define interfaces in inner layers (repositories, gateways), implement in outer layers, use Dependency Injection (pass dependencies from outer to inner, e.g., DI framework like Hilt, Koin), keep entities pure (no framework dependencies), one use case per feature (GetUserUseCase, UpdateUserUseCase). When to use: large apps (many features, long lifespan), teams (clear boundaries reduce conflicts), enterprise (strict requirements, maintainability critical). When to skip: MVPs (speed over architecture), simple apps (few screens, basic CRUD), small teams (communication easy, less need for strict boundaries). Conclusion: Clean Architecture powerful for scalable mobile apps, dependency rule ensures flexibility and testability, requires discipline and planning upfront.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (338, 'Explain modular architecture in mobile apps. How do you structure a large app into modules?',
     'Modular architecture: breaking monolithic app into smaller, independent modules, improves build times, enforces separation, enables feature teams. Benefits: (1) Build performance - only changed modules rebuild, parallel compilation, Gradle/Xcode incremental builds faster. (2) Separation of concerns - clear boundaries between features, enforced by module dependencies (can't access internals). (3) Reusability - common modules shared across apps (design system, networking). (4) Team scalability - teams own modules, less merge conflicts, independent development. (5) Testing - modules testable in isolation, faster test execution (test only affected modules). Module types: (1) App module - entry point, depends on all feature modules, minimal code (just composition). (2) Feature modules - self-contained features (login, profile, checkout), independent navigation/UI. (3) Core modules - shared code (networking, database, analytics), no UI. (4) Common/shared - utilities, extensions, base classes. Dependency rules: Feature modules shouldn't depend on each other (prevents coupling), use abstraction (dependency inversion), features depend on core (networking, models), app module assembles everything (DI container). Example Android structure: :app (MainActivity, Application, DI setup), :feature:login (LoginActivity, LoginViewModel), :feature:profile (ProfileFragment, ProfileVM), :core:network (Retrofit, API interfaces), :core:database (Room, DAOs), :common (extensions, utils). Build.gradle dependencies: feature:login depends on core:network, common; app depends on all features. Benefits: changing login doesn''t rebuild profile. Example iOS structure: App target (AppDelegate, SceneDelegate), LoginKit framework (screens, view models), ProfileKit, CoreNetworking (API client), DesignSystem (UI components). Linking: app links all frameworks. Communication between modules: (1) Dependency Inversion - shared interfaces in core, implementations in features, example: protocol CartService in core:cart-api, implementation in feature:cart, other features depend on protocol. (2) Navigation coordinator - central coordinator knows about all features, features request navigation via protocol, prevents direct dependencies. (3) Event bus - publish-subscribe (EventBus, NotificationCenter), loose coupling but harder to trace. (4) Deep links - features register URL handlers, navigate via URLs, platform-agnostic. Challenges: ( 1) Initial overhead - setting up module structure upfront, tooling configuration. (2) Over-modularization - too many tiny modules hard to navigate, balance needed. (3) Circular dependencies - features depend on each other (requires refactoring to shared module). (4) Duplicate code - temptation to duplicate instead of extracting to shared module. Best practices: start with coarse modules (don't over-modularize initially), extract common code early (avoid duplication debt), define clear APIs (public interfaces, internal implementations), enforce with linting (dependency graph validation tools), use dynamic feature modules (Android, on-demand delivery). Android-specific: dynamic feature modules (Google Play downloads on-demand), reduces APK size, example: game levels as separate modules. Gradle: com.android.dynamic-feature plugin. iOS-specific: Swift Package Manager growing (replacing CocoaPods), local packages for modules, XcodeGen for managing complex projects (generated from YAML). Build time optimization: module dependency graph visualization (find bottlenecks), parallel builds (Gradle --parallel, Xcode build settings), precompiled modules (speeds subsequent builds). When to modularize: apps with >50k lines code, teams >5 developers, features developed independently (airline, banking, e-commerce apps). When to wait: early-stage apps (architecture evolving), small codebases (<10k lines), solo developer (overhead not justified). Conclusion: modular architecture essential for large mobile apps, improves builds, team scalability, maintainability, requires planning but pays off long-term.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (339, 'What is Dependency Injection in mobile development? Compare different DI approaches (manual, Syringe,  Hilt, Koin).',
     'Dependency Injection: design pattern providing objects (dependencies) from outside instead of creating internally, promotes loose coupling, testability. Without DI: class ViewModel { private let service = NetworkService() }, tightly coupled (can''t test without real network), hard to replace implementation. With DI: class ViewModel { private let service: NetworkServiceProtocol; init(service: NetworkServiceProtocol) { self.service = service } }, dependency injected (constructor, property, method), easily mocked for tests. Manual DI: manually create and pass dependencies. iOS example: let service = NetworkService(); let viewModel = ViewModel(service: service). Android: register in Application() { val service = NetworkService(); val viewModel = ViewModel(service) }. Pros: simple, explicit, no framework. Cons: boilerplate (manual wiring), error-prone (forgot to pass dependency), doesn''t scale (deep dependency trees). Service Locator (anti-pattern often confused with DI): ServiceLocator.shared.register(NetworkService()); class ViewModel { let service = ServiceLocator.shared.resolve(NetworkServiceProtocol) }, pulls dependencies (not pushed), hides dependencies (not visible in init), harder to test. Swinject (iOS): popular DI framework. Register dependencies: let container = Container(); container.register(NetworkServiceProtocol.self) { _ in NetworkService() }; container.register(ViewModel.self) { r in ViewModel(service: r.resolve(NetworkServiceProtocol.self)!) }. Resolve: let viewModel = container.resolve(ViewModel.self). Features: lifetimes (transient, singleton, container-specific), circular dependency resolution. Pros: mature, flexible. Cons: runtime resolution (type safety issues), boilerplate. Hilt (Android): Jetpack library, built on Dagger, compile-time DI. Annotations: @HiltAndroidApp on Application; @AndroidEntryPoint on Activity/Fragment; @Inject constructor(val service: NetworkService); @Module + @Provides for interfaces. Example: @Provides fun provideNetworkService(): NetworkService = Retrofit.create(...); @Inject automatically injects. Pros: compile-time safety (errors at build), no runtime overhead, Google supported. Cons: annotation processing (slower builds), learning curve (Dagger complexity). Koin (Android/Kotlin Multiplatform): lightweight, DSL-based, runtime DI. Module definition: val appModule = module { single { NetworkService() }; factory { ViewModel(get()) } }. Start: startKoin { modules(appModule) }. Inject: by inject() or get(). Pros: simple DSL (readable), fast setup, KMP support. Cons: runtime resolution (crashes if misconfigured), slight performance overhead. Comparison: Manual DI - simple apps, full control, no framework. Swinject (iOS) - medium apps, need flexibility, okay with runtime resolution. Hilt (Android) - large apps, want compile safety, standard Android. Koin - rapid development, KMP apps, simplicity over compile safety. Best practices: constructor injection preferred (dependencies explicit), interface-based (inject protocols/interfaces, not concrete classes), singleton vs transient (network client singleton, ViewModels transient), scoping (ViewModel scope to Activity, repository to Application), test doubles (inject mocks in tests, easy with DI). DI and testing: with DI: override container in tests, inject fakes/mocks: testContainer.register { MockNetworkService() }, ViewModel uses mock, tests isolated. Without DI: can''t easily replace NetworkService, integration test at best (slow, flaky). When to use DI: medium to large apps (many dependencies, complex graphs), testability important (unit tests without real implementations), team development (clear dependency contracts), modular architecture (features depend on abstractions). When to skip: tiny apps (few dependencies, manual DI suffices), prototypes (speed over architecture). iOS modern: SwiftUI has @EnvironmentObject (built-in DI of sorts): .environmentObject(viewModel) injects down tree, simple cases sufficient. Android modern: Hilt standard for new projects (Jetpack recommendation), replaces Dagger boilerplate. Conclusion: DI essential for testable, maintainable mobile apps, choose framework based on app size, team preference, manual DI underrated for simple cases.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (340, 'Your mobile app has grown to 100K+ lines of code with 15 developers working simultaneously. Build times have increased to 20+ minutes for full builds, and teams frequently face merge conflicts in shared files. Module boundaries are unclear, leading to tangled dependencies. How would you restructure the app architecture to improve build times, enable parallel development, and enforce modularity? Discuss modularization strategies, dependency management, and tooling.',
     'Problem analysis: 20-minute builds = productivity killer (context switching, waiting), merge conflicts = unclear ownership/boundaries, tangled dependencies = tight coupling (can''t change module without breaking others), 100K+ lines in monolith = build system compiles everything always. Goals: reduce build time <5 minutes incremental builds, eliminate merge conflicts via module ownership, enforce dependency rules (prevent coupling), enable parallel team development. Diagnosis phase: (1) Build analysis - Android: gradle --profile (HTML report shows bottlenecks), identify slowest tasks (compilation, linting, resource processing), iOS: Xcode build timeline analyze (which targets take longest). (2) Dependency graph visualization - Gradle: ./gradlew projectDependencies > deps.txt, visualize with tools like Gradle Enterprise, identify circular dependencies, overly-connected modules. (3) Module coupling analysis - scan import statements (who imports whom), identify god classes (imported everywhere), find feature coupling (LoginActivity importing CheckoutFragment). (4) Team workflow analysis - review PR conflicts (which files/modules clash), identify high-traffic files (ApplicationClass, Constants, BaseActivity = red flags), survey team pain points. Likely findings: single :app module contains 80% code (features not separated), shared :common module with everything (utils, models, base classes), becomes dependency hub, features import each other directly (Home imports Profile imports Settings = spaghetti), generated code (databinding, dagger) not cached (regenerates full builds). Modularization strategy: Phase 1 - Extract core infrastructure: (1) Create :core:network module (API client, interceptors, base DTOs), all features depend on it (acceptable). (2) Create :core:database (Room/Realm, DAOs, entities), persistence abstraction. (3) Create :core:logging, :core:analytics - cross-cutting concerns, depended by all. (4) Create :designsystem - UI components, styles, themes, enables consistent UI, prevents duplication. Benefit: core modules rarely change (stable), when do change (API client update), only core rebuilds initially, features rebuild incrementally (cache valid if APIs same). Phase 2 - Extract feature modules: (1) Identify features - Login, Home, Profile, Settings, Checkout, etc., each becomes module. (2) Create :feature:login - LoginActivity, LoginViewModel, login-specific layouts, depends only on :core (network, analytics). (3) Extract each feature similarly - :feature:profile, :feature:checkout. (4) Feature-to-feature communication via interfaces - create :core:navigation (deep link coordinator), create :feature:login:api (public interfaces for login), :feature:checkout depends on :login:api (not implementation), enforces decoupling. Benefit: team owns feature module (login team = :feature:login), changes isolated (editing profile doesn''t rebuild checkout), parallel development (teams work simultaneously without conflicts). Phase 3 - Enforce dependency rules: (1) Dependency graph policy - features DON'T depend on other features directly, features depend on :core and own :api modules, :app module depends on all features (composition root). (2) Gradle dependency constraints - use API vs implementation carefully: implementation doesn''t leak to consumers (faster builds), api leaks (use only for :api modules). (3) Linting rules - custom lint checks fail build if feature imports other feature directly, tools like dependency-guard plugin (enforces graphDeprecated configurations). Example violation caught: :feature:profile imports :feature:login.LoginActivity → build fails → refactor to :login:api interface. Android-specific optimizations: (1) Enable Gradle build cache - org.gradle.caching=true, shares build outputs across branches, first build slow, subsequent fast (reuses cache). (2) Configuration cache - org.gradle.unsafe.configuration-cache=true (Gradle 8+), caches configuration phase (huge speedup). (3) Incremental annotation processing - kapt.incremental.apt=true, Room, Dagger process incrementally. (4) Kotlin compile avoidance - use implementation (not api) where possible, changing internal implementation doesn''t recompile consumers. (5) BuildSrc vs composite builds - move gradle build logic to included builds (faster than buildSrc). (6) Parallel builds - org.gradle.parallel=true, --max-workers=8, builds independent modules simultaneously. (7) Dynamic feature modules - large features (video player, premium) as DFMs, reduces base APK, download on-demand, faster builds (not always compiled). iOS-specific optimizations: (1) Modularize via frameworks/Swift packages - create LoginKit.framework, ProfileKit, each with own target, Xcode compiles targets in parallel (better CPU utilization). (2) Explicit module maps - module.modulemap files, faster compilation, better incremental builds. (3) Whole module optimization - only for release builds, debug: incremental, release: optimize whole module. (4) Build time analyzer - xcode-build-times (shows per-file timings), identify slow Swift files (complex generics, type inference), refactor bottlenecks. (5) Derived data management - clean periodically, use Xcode build system (new, parallel), CCCache  for C/ObjC (speeds subsequent builds). Dependency management: (1) Version catalogs (Gradle) - centralize versions: libs.versions.toml, all modules reference same versions, consistency,no conflicts. (2) CocoaPods/SPM (iOS) - modularize dependencies (networking pod, UI pod), faster updates (only changed pods rebuild). (3) Dependency substitution - testing: substitute :feature:login with test double, build only test scope. Team workflow improvements: (1) Code ownership - .github/CODEOWNERS: feature/login/** @login-team, PRs auto-assigned, clear accountability. (2) Feature flags - merge incomplete features behind flag (no long-lived branches), reduces merge conflicts. (3) Trunk-based development - short-lived branches (<1 day), frequent integration, modules help isolation. (4) CI/CD optimization - affected module detection: only run tests/linting for changed modules + dependents, example: :feature:login changed → test :login and :app (depends on it),  skip :profile tests. Tooling integration: (1) Gradle Enterprise (Android) - build scans (shared URL of build), performance trending (track build time regression), cache analytics (cache hit rate). (2) Bazel/Buck (advanced) - ultra-fast incremental builds, fine-grained dependency tracking, steep learning curve, Netflix, Uber scale. (3) Module graph visualization - dependency-tree-diff visualizes changes impact, communicates architecture to team. (4) Pre-merge builds - CI builds modules affected by PR, catches breakages before merge, gated commits. Migration execution: (1) Week 1-2: Extract core modules - low risk (infrastructure), high value (depended by all). (2) Week 3-6: Extract 2-3 pilot features - pick isolated features first (profile, settings), learn/iterate on module structure. (3) Week 7-12: Remaining features - parallel extraction (teams extract owned features), daily syncs (resolve integration issues). (4) Week 13-14: Cleanup - delete dead code (emerged during extraction), optimize dependency graph, document module boundaries. (5) Ongoing: Enforce rules - CI checks, code review guidelines, refactor when violations occur. Measuring success: Build time reduction: full build 20min → 8min (compilation bottlenecks removed), incremental builds 20min → 2min (only 10% modules rebuild typical change), clean builds improved via caching (second build 5min from cache). Merge conflicts: 10/week → 1/week (teams in separate modules). Code ownership: every module has owner (clear in CODEOWNERS). Team velocity: features delivered 30% faster (parallel development). Developer satisfaction: survey shows reduced frustration. Risks and mitigation: (1) Over-modularization - too many tiny modules hard to navigate, mitigation: start coarse-grained (10-15 modules), refine over time. (2) Interface explosion - every feature needs :api module, boilerplate overhead, mitigation: only create :api when feature used by others (not upfront). (3) Breaking changes in :core - changes to network module break all features, mitigation: semantic versioning :core modules, deprecation policy (old + new API coexist temporarily), comprehensive :core testing. (4) Team resistance - change is hard, "worked fine before", mitigation: pilot with willing team (prove value), celebrate wins (share build time improvements), training sessions. Expected outcome: After 3 months: build time reduced 75% (20min → 5min incremental), teams develop independently (merge conflicts rare), clear module boundaries enforced (CI checks), scalable architecture (can add teams/features without slowing down), onboarding easier (new devs work in isolated module).',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

    -- Topic 69: Mobile Security (5 questions)
    (341, 'What is SSL pinning in mobile apps? How does it protect against man-in-the-middle attacks?',
     'SSL Pinning (Certificate Pinning): hardcodes expected server certificate/public key in app, rejects connections if certificate doesn''t match, prevents MITM (Man-In-The-Middle) attacks even with compromised CA. Normal SSL/TLS: device trusts certificate authorities (CAs), server presents certificate signed by CA, device verifies CA signature, if valid CA (in device trust store), connection accepted. MITM attack: attacker installs rogue CA certificate on device (physical access, social engineering), proxies traffic through own certificate (signed by rogue CA), device trusts it (rogue CA in trust store), attacker decrypts traffic. Certificate pinning defense: app contains hash of expected server certificate or public key, during SSL handshake, app receives server certificate, computes hash, compares with pinned hash, if match → proceed; if mismatch → reject (prevent MITM). Implementation approaches: (1) Certificate pinning - pin entire certificate: hardcode myserver.crt hash in app, strict (pin exact certificate), must update app when certificate rotates (typically yearly). (2) Public key pinning - pin public key only: extract public key from certificate, pin key hash, flexible (certificate can rotate if same key), longer validity but must rotate on key compromise. iOS implementation: URLSession with custom delegate: func urlSession(_ session: URLSession, didReceive challenge: URLAuthenticationChallenge, completionHandler: (URLSession.AuthChallengeDisposition, URLCredential?) -> Void) { // validate certificate against pinned hash }. Libraries: TrustKit (easy pinning, handles rotation). Android: Network Security Config (XML): <network-security-config><pin-set><pin digest="sha256">base64hash</pin></pin-set></network-security-config>. Libraries: OkHttp CertificatePinner: val pinner = CertificatePinner.Builder().add("api.example.com", "sha256/hash...").build(). Challenges: (1) Certificate rotation - certificates expire, must update app with new pin before old expires, grace period (pin old + new), over-the-air config (fetch pins remotely, backup if hardcoded). (2) Breaking updates - wrong pin bricks app (can''t connect), testing critical (test pinning in staging), fallback mechanisms (detect widespread failures, temporarily disable). (3) Proxy tools blocked - Charles, Fiddler used for debugging, can''t intercept pinned traffic, disable pinning debug builds (#ifdef DEBUG). Best practices: pin public key not certificate (longer lifetime), pin intermediate CA or root (more stable than leaf certificate), backup pins (primary + backup public keys in case primary compromised), expiration policy (pins with expiry dates, fetch new remotely), monitor failures (analytics on pin validation failures, detect broad issues). When to use pinning: high-security apps (banking, healthcare, payments), sensitive data transmission, compliance requirements (PCI-DSS recommends). When to skip: standard apps (e-commerce, social), pinning overhead not justified, certificate rotation burden, proxy debugging important (development). Alternatives: mutual TLS (client certificate authentication), end-to-end encryption (decrypt only on client/server, MITM sees encrypted), obfuscation (makes attacks harder but not impossible). Conclusion: SSL pinning strong MITM protection, requires careful implementation and operational planning (certificate rotation), use for sensitive apps, balance security with maintenance overhead.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),


    (342, 'How do you securely store sensitive data like tokens and passwords in mobile apps?',
     'Never store in plain text: SharedPreferences (Android), UserDefaults (iOS) unencrypted, easily extracted from device backup or rooted/jailbroken devices, reverse engineering can read. Secure storage solutions: iOS - Keychain: hardware-backed (Secure Enclave on modern devices), encrypted, survives app uninstall (optionally), usage: let query: [String: Any] = [kSecClass as String: kSecClassGenericPassword, kSecAttrAccount: "userToken", kSecValueData: tokenData]; SecItemAdd(query).Libraries: KeychainAccess wrapper (simpler API). Keychain accessibility: kSecAttrAccessibleWhenUnlocked (default, accessible when device unlocked), kSecAttrAccessibleAfterFirstUnlock (background tasks), kSecAttrAccessibleAlways (avoid, least secure). Biometric protection: kSecAttrAccessControl with biometry flags, requires Face ID/Touch ID to access. Android - Keystore: hardware-backed TEE (Trusted Execution Environment) on modern devices, keys never leave, encrypt data with Keystore key. Usage: generate key in Keystore: val keyGenerator = KeyGenerator.getInstance(KeyProperties.KEY_ALGORITHM_AES, "AndroidKeyStore"); keyGenerator.init(spec); val key = keyGenerator.generateKey(). Encrypt data with key: val cipher = Cipher.getInstance("AES/GCM/NoPadding"); cipher.init(Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE, key); val encrypted = cipher.doFinal(data). Store encrypted data in SharedPreferences. Decrypt on retrieval. Android JetpackSecurity: EncryptedSharedPreferences (wraps Keystore automatically), easy API: val sharedPreferences = EncryptedSharedPreferences.create(context, "secure_prefs", masterKey, EncryptedSharedPreferences.PrefKeyEncryptionScheme.AES256_SIV, EncryptedSharedPreferences.PrefValueEncryptionScheme.AES256_GCM); sharedPreferences.edit().putString("token", token).apply(). EncryptedFile for file encryption. Best practices: (1) Never store passwords - store tokens instead (OAuth, JWT), tokens revocable, passwords aren''t; if must store password (legacy), encrypt with Keychain/Keystore. (2) Short-lived tokens - access token expires quickly (1 hour), refresh token rotates, limits exposure. (3) Biometric authentication - require biometry for accessing sensitive data (not just app unlock), example: transaction confirmation. (4) Token rotation - refresh tokens periodically, detect theft (concurrent sessions invalidated). (5) Obfuscation - additional layer (not primary security), makes reverse engineering harder, tools: ProGuard (Android), obfuscation tools (iOS). Common mistakes: (1) Hardcoded secrets - API keys in source code, easily extracted from binary, solution: backend-driven (fetch keys), environment-specific build configs. (2) Logging secrets - Log.d("Token: " + token), visible in logcat, appears in crash reports, solution: redact in prod (strip logs), lint checks forbid logging "token", "password". (3) Insecure transmission - sending tokens over HTTP (not HTTPS), MITM exposure, solution: always HTTPS, certificate pinning. (4) Screenshot/clipboard leaks - sensitive screens capturable (screenshots, screen recording), keyboard autofill caches passwords, solution: FLAG_SECURE (Android blocks screenshots), disable autofill for sensitive fields. Data residency: (1) Memory - clear sensitive data after use: token = null; data structures zeroed. (2) Caches - don''t cache sensitive responses (HTTP cache headers), NSURLCache/OkHttp cache could store unencrypted. (3) Backups -exclude secure data from device backups: allowBackup="false" (Android), BackupItemKey settings (iOS). (4) OS integration - exclude from app switcher previews (hide sensitive content when backgrounded). Testing: (1) Rooted/jailbroken devices - test app can''t be bypassed on compromised devices, root detection (controversial, determined attackers bypass), graceful degradation (limit features not block entirely). (2) Network interception - Charles Proxy attempts (with pinning, should fail), verify encrypted data transit. (3) Static analysis - reverse engineer APK/IPA, confirm secrets not in plaintext, obfuscation effective. (4) Penetration testing - security audit by pros, identifies storage vulnerabilities. When to use what: Tokens, API keys - Keychain/Keystore (encrypted, hardware-backed). User preferences (non-sensitive) - UserDefaults/SharedPreferences (convenience). Large files - EncryptedFile/Data Protection APIs. Biometric auth - Keychain/Keystore with access control. Conclusion: use platform-provided secure storage (Keychain, Keystore), never roll own crypto, layer defenses (encryption + obfuscation + secure transmission), test on compromised devices, regular security audits.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (343, 'What are common mobile app security vulnerabilities? How do you prevent them?',
     'OWASP Mobile Top 10: (1) Improper Platform Usage - misusing iOS/Android security features, example: incorrect keychain usage, insecure file permissions. Prevention: follow platform guidelines, use security APIs correctly, code review. (2) Insecure Data Storage - sensitive data in plaintext (logs, cache, databases, backups). Prevention: Keychain/Keystore for secrets, encrypt databases (SQLCipher, Realm encryption), exclude backups (allowBackup=false), clear logs in production. (3) Insecure Communication - HTTP instead of HTTPS, weak TLS versions, no certificate validation. Prevention: enforce HTTPS (App Transport Security iOS, Network Security Config Android), TLS 1.2+, certificate pinning, disable cleartext traffic. (4) Insecure Authentication - weak session management, no rate limiting, credential storage issues. Prevention: OAuth 2.0/OpenID Connect (not basic auth), biometric authentication, secure token storage, session timeout, multi-factor. (5) Insufficient Cryptography - weak algorithms (MD5, SHA1, DES), hardcoded keys, improper IV usage. Prevention: use platform crypto APIs (CommonCrypto, Keystore), AES-256, secure random IVs, never hardcode keys, HTTPS for key exchange. (6) Insecure Authorization - improper access controls, insecure direct object references. Prevention: validate permissions server-side, check user owns resource (not just authenticated), principle of least privilege. (7) Client Code Quality - buffer overflows, format string vulnerabilities. Prevention: safe languages (Swift, Kotlin over C), input validation, static analysis (SonarQube, Checkmarx). (8) Code Tampering - app modified/repackaged (malware injected). Prevention: code signing (iOS automatic, Android jarsigner), root/jailbreak detection, integrity checks (hash verifications), obfuscation. (9) Reverse Engineering - decompiling APK/IPA to steal algorithms/keys. Prevention: obfuscation (ProGuard, R8, obfuscators), strip symbols, critical logic server-side (not client), anti-debug techniques. (10) Extraneous Functionality - debug code in production, backdoors, test endpoints. Prevention: build variants (debug vs release), feature flags, code review, automated checks (lint for Log.d in release). Specific vulnerabilities: SQL Injection - concatenating user input in queries: cursor = db.rawQuery("SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '" + userInput + "'"). Prevention: parameterized queries (Room, prepared statements). XSS in WebViews - displaying user content without sanitization in WebView. Prevention: validate/sanitize input, disable JavaScript if not needed, Content Security Policy. Deep Link exploits - unvalidated deep links trigger sensitive actions. Prevention: validate intent data, require user confirmation for sensitive actions, use App Links (verified). Clipboard hijacking - malware monitors clipboard for sensitive data (crypto addresses). Prevention: clear clipboard after use, warn users, short clipboard lifetime. Screenshot leaks - sensitive screens captured, visible in app switcher. Prevention: FLAG_SECURE (Android), hide sensitive content when backgrounded. Local file inclusion - app reads arbitrary files based on user input. Prevention: whitelist allowed paths, sandbox file access. Side channel attacks - timing attacks (login timing reveals valid usernames). Prevention: constant-time comparisons, rate limiting, captchas. Security checklist: (1) Network - HTTPS everywhere, certificate pinning (high-security), no hardcoded URLs (config-driven). (2) Storage - Keychain/Keystore for secrets, encrypted databases, no logs/backups of sensitive data. (3) Authentication - secure token management, biometric where applicable, session timeout, logout functionality. (4) Code - obfuscation (release builds), no debug code, ProGuard/R8 enabled, code signing. (5) Permissions - request minimal permissions, explain why (privacy), runtime permissions (Android 6+). (6) Third-party libraries - audit dependencies (known vulnerabilities), keep updated, minimize (attack surface). (7) API security - validate inputs, rate limiting, CORS policies, authentication required. Testing: (1) Static analysis - tools find hardcoded secrets, insecure APIs, lint rules. (2) Dynamic analysis - runtime behavior, proxy traffic (Burp Suite), fuzzing. (3) Penetration testing - ethical hackers, simulate real attacks, comprehensive audit. (4) Automated scanning - SAST/DAST tools (Veracode, Checkmarx, MobSF). (5) Bug bounty - crowd-sourced security, incentivizes disclosure. Compliance: PCI-DSS (payment apps), HIPAA (health), GDPR (data privacy), app store guidelines (App Store Review, Google Play), encrypt sensitive data, secure transmission. Conclusion: security is multi-layered (defense in depth), use platform security features, keep dependencies updated, regular audits, educate team (secure coding practices), security by design (not afterthought).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (344, 'Explain mobile app code obfuscation. What are the trade-offs?',
     'Code obfuscation: transforms code to make reverse engineering difficult while preserving functionality, renames symbols, removes metadata, restructures control flow. Purpose: protect intellectual property (algorithms, business logic), delay attackers (not foolproof but raises bar), hide API keys/endpoints (mild security, don''t rely solely). Obfuscation techniques: (1) Name obfuscation - renames classes, methods, variables to meaningless names. Original: class UserAuthentication { func validateToken() }, obfuscated: class a { func b() }. Attackers can''t infer purpose by name. (2) String encryption - encrypts string literals, decrypts at runtime. API URLs, keys less visible. (3) Control flow obfuscation - inserts bogus code paths, unconditional jumps, opaque predicates (always true/false). Makes code harder to follow. (4) Dead code injection - adds unreachable code (distracts analyzers). (5) Resource obfuscation - renames resources (images, layouts). (6) Anti-debugging - detects debuggers attached, checks for instruments. Tools: Android - ProGuard (legacy, basic name obfuscation + shrinking): minifyEnabled true, proguardFiles. R8 (modern, default since AGP 3.4+): shrinks + obfuscates + optimizes, faster than ProGuard, integrated Gradle. DexGuard (commercial, advanced): string encryption, anti-tampering, resource encryption. iOS - No official obfuscator (Apple doesn''t provide), third-party tools: iXGuard, Obfuscator-iOS (Swift obfuscation), manual techniques: rename symbols, strip debugging symbols (release builds automatic), class-dump protection (obfuscate Objective-C interfaces). Swift harder to reverse than Objective-C (no runtime introspection), but still decompilable. Trade-offs: Pros: (1) IP protection - delays reverse engineering (hours to days to weeks), competitive advantage protected temporarily. (2) Attacker deterrence - raises effort required, might move to easier targets. (3) Compliance - some industries require code protection. Cons: (1) Debugging harder - obfuscated stack traces meaningless: at a.b(Unknown Source) vs UserAuthentication.validateToken(UserAuthentication.kt:42). Must use mapping files (ProGuard mapping.txt) to deobfuscate crashes. (2) Build time increase - obfuscation adds processing overhead (R8 optimized, less impact). (3) Not foolproof - determined attacker will eventually succeed (obfuscation delays, doesn''t prevent, dynamic analysis bypasses static obfuscation). (4) Reflection breaks - dynamically accessed classes can be obfuscated away, example: Class.forName("com.app.UserService") fails if UserService renamed. Must use keep rules: -keep class com.app.UserService. (5) Library compatibility - some libraries use reflection, need keep rules, trial-and-error finding rules. (6) Maintenance overhead - keep rules file grows, must update when adding dependencies, test thoroughly post-obfuscation (functionality preserved). Best practices: (1) Obfuscate release builds only - debug builds unobfuscated (development speed), release obfuscated (production). (2) Preserve stack traces - upload ProGuard mapping to crash reporting (Firebase Crashlytics, Sentry), automatically deobfuscates. (3) Keep essential classes - public APIs, serialization classes, native methods: -keep public class com.app.sdk.** { public *; }. (4) Test extensively - integration tests on release builds, catch runtime errors from obfuscation. (5) Version mapping files - archive mapping.txt per release version, essential for deobfuscating old crashes. (6) Combine with other security - obfuscation + root detection + SSL pinning + server-side logic = layered defense. Limitations: (1) Native code not obfuscated - JNI libraries (C/C++) visible (use NDK obfuscators). (2) Resources partially protected - strings in XML still readable (string encryption tools). (3) Dynamic analysis - runtime behavior observable (debuggers, hooking frameworks like Frida), obfuscation doesn''t hide. (4) Open source - if using open source libraries, attacker knows those parts. Alternatives/complementary: (1) Server-side logic - keep critical algorithms server-side (not client), client calls API, intellectual property stays server. (2) Tamper detection - app detects if modified (checksum verification), exits or limits functionality. (3) Jailbreak/root detection - refuses to run on compromised devices (controversial, determined users bypass). (4) Code splitting - critical parts loaded dynamically (harder to analyze statically). When to use: Commercial apps (paid apps, games with proprietary engines), Financial apps (fraud prevention algorithms), Apps with hardcoded secrets (migrate to backend ideally, obfuscate as mitigation), Competitive advantage (unique algorithms). When to skip: Open source apps (source available anyway), Apps with all logic server-side (client just UI), Small utility apps (low value target), Performance-critical (obfuscation adds slight overhead). Conclusion: obfuscation useful layer in defense-in-depth strategy, delays but doesn''t prevent reverse engineering, essential to preserve crash reporting (mapping files), biggest value in combination with other security measures (server-side logic, pinning, detection), balance protection with maintainability.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (345, 'Your mobile banking app needs to meet strict security compliance (PCI-DSS for payments, SOC 2). Security audit found several vulnerabilities: tokens stored in SharedPreferences/UserDefaults (unencrypted), API calls over HTTP in legacy modules, no root/jailbreak detection, hardcoded API keys in source code, and screenshots enabled on sensitive screens. How would you systematically remediate these vulnerabilities while maintaining app functionality? Discuss secure storage, network security, anti-tampering, and compliance validation.',
     'Vulnerability assessment severity: Unencrypted token storage = CRITICAL (credential theft if device compromised), HTTP API calls = CRITICAL (MITM attacks, data interception), hardcoded API keys = HIGH (keys extracted by reverse engineering), no root/jailbreak detection = MEDIUM (compromised environment detection), screenshot enabled = MEDIUM (data leakage via device backups/malware). Compliance impact: all violate PCI-DSS Requirement 4 (encrypt transmission), Requirement 3 (protect stored cardholder data), SOC 2 CC6 (logical access), failures block app store approval/payment processor certification. Remediation roadmap: Phase 1 - Critical fixes (Week 1-2): Fix 1: Migrate token storage to secure keychain/keystore. Android implementation: (a) Add Jetpack Security dependency: implementation "androidx.security:security-crypto:1.1.0-alpha06". (b) Create EncryptedSharedPreferences: val masterKey = MasterKey.Builder(context).setKeyScheme(MasterKey.KeyScheme.AES256_GCM).build(); val encryptedPrefs = EncryptedSharedPreferences.create(context, "secure_prefs", masterKey, ...). (c) Migration script: read old tokens from SharedPreferences, write to EncryptedSharedPreferences, delete from old storage: val oldToken = oldPrefs.getString("access_token", null); if (oldToken != null) { encryptedPrefs.edit().putString("access_token", oldToken).apply(); oldPrefs.edit().remove("access_token").apply() }. (d) Update all token read/write code paths (search codebase for SharedPref usage, replace with encrypted version). iOS implementation: (a) Migrate to Keychain: let query: [String: Any] = [kSecClass: kSecClassGenericPassword, kSecAttrService: "com.app.banking", kSecAttrAccount: "accessToken", kSecAttrAccessible: kSecAttrAccessibleWhenUnlocked, kSecValueData: tokenData]; SecItemAdd(query). (b) Migration: read UserDefaults tokens, write to Keychain, delete UserDefaults: if let token = UserDefaults.get("token") { saveToKeychain(token); UserDefaults.removeObject(forKey: "token") }. (c) Add biometric protection for sensitive operations: kSecAttrAccessControl with biometry flags, require Face ID for txn confirmation. Testing: verify tokens in secure storage (inspect app data, confirm not in UserDefaults/SharedPrefs), test migration path (upgrade from old version, tokens preserved), test on rooted/jailbroken device (extract filesystem, verify tokens encrypted/inaccessible). Fix 2: Enforce HTTPS across all network calls. Android implementation: (a) Network Security Config (res/xml/network_security_config.xml): <network-security-config><base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="false" /></network-security-config>, blocks all HTTP. (b) Manifest reference: android:networkSecurityConfig="@xml/network_security_config". (c) Identify legacy HTTP endpoints: search codebase for "http://" (not "https://"), audit OkHttp/Retrofit configurations. (d) Update endpoints: change baseURL to HTTPS in Retrofit: Retrofit.Builder().baseUrl("https://api.bank.com"). (e) Backend coordination: ensure all endpoints support HTTPS (TLS 1.2+, valid certificates), test staging environment first. iOS implementation: (a) App Transport Security (ATS) enabled bydefault, ensure no exceptions in Info.plist: remove NSAllowsArbitraryLoads or NSExceptionDomains that allow HTTP. (b) Audit URLSession calls: search for "http://" URLs, replace with HTTPS. (c) Certificate pinning for critical endpoints (optional but recommended for banking): use TrustKit or custom URLSessionDelegate to pin public keys. Testing: attempt HTTP call (should fail with error like CLEARTEXT communication not permitted), verify all API interactions HTTPS (Charles Proxy inspection, look for encrypted traffic), certificate validation (expired/untrusted cert should fail, valid cert proceed). Fix 3: Remove hardcoded API keys from source. (a) Audit codebase: search for API key patterns (regex: [A-Za-z0-9]{32,}), identify hardcoded secrets (API keys, client secrets, encryption keys). (b) Move to backend: critical keys fetched from backend on app launch (authenticated endpoint), example: POST /api/config returns { paymentGatewayKey: "..." }, needs auth token (so public can''t call). (c) Environment-based configuration: non-sensitive config (API base URLs) in build configs, Gradle: buildConfigField "String", "API_URL", "\"https://api.prod.bank.com\"", accessed via BuildConfig.API_URL. iOS: xcconfig files or build settings, accessed via Bundle.main.infoDictionary. (d) Obfuscation for client-side keys: if key must stay client (Analytics SDK key, Map API key), obfuscate (encrypt in binary, decrypt runtime), native code storage (harder to extract than Java/Swift), note: obfuscation NOT security, prevents casual extraction only. (e) Git history cleanup: if secrets committed historically, scrub git history (git filter-branch, BFG repo-cleaner), rotate exposed secrets immediately. Testing: reverse engineer APK/IPA (apktool, class-dump), search for API key strings (should not find plaintext), monitor backend /config endpoint (ensure requires authentication, rate limited). Phase 2 - High priority (Week 3): Fix 4: Implement root/jailbreak detection. Android root detection: (a) Check for su binary: File("/system/xbin/su").exists() || File("/system/bin/su").exists(). (b) Check for Magisk, SuperSU apps: packageManager.getPackageInfo("com.topjohnwu.magisk"). (c) Check build tags: Build.TAGS?.contains("test-keys"). (d) SafetyNet Attestation API (Google): comprehensive check, server-side validation of device integrity: SafetyNetClient.attest(nonce, apiKey).addOnSuccessListener { response -> /* verify response server-side */ }. iOS jailbreak detection: (a) Check for Cydia app: UIApplication.shared.canOpenURL(URL(string: "cydia://")). (b) Check writable system directories: FileManager.default.isWritableFile(atPath: "/private/var"). (c) Check for installed jailbreak files: FileManager.fileExists(atPath: "/bin/bash"). (d) Fork detection: attempt fork() (should fail on non-jailbroken): fork() returns != -1 = jailbroken. Response strategy: Don''t hard-block (determined users bypass, bad PR), graceful degradation: display warning "Running on rooted device, security compromised, proceed at own risk", disable sensitive features (P2P transfers, high-value txns), increased monitoring (log rooted sessions separately, fraud detection flags). Testing: test on rooted/jailbroken device (detection triggers), test on normal device (no false positives), test bypass resistance (common bypass tools, detection still works). Fix 5: Disable screenshots on sensitive screens. Android: (a) Sensitive activities (login, account details, txn confirmation): getWindow().setFlags(WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_SECURE, WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_SECURE) in onCreate. (b) Prevents screenshots, screen recording, app previews in Recents. (c) Selective application: only sensitive screens (not entire app, UX balance). iOS: (a) Hide content when backgrounded: NotificationCenter.default.addObserver(..., name: UIApplication.willResignActiveNotification...) { hideContentView.isHidden = false }, shows placeholder when app switcher opened. (b) Screenshot notification: listen UIApplication.userDidTakeScreenshotNotification, log analytics (potential data theft indicator). (c) No native way to prevent screenshots (iOS doesn''t provide), hide content in app switcher prevents preview leakage. Testing: attempt screenshot on sensitive screen (Android: fails or blank, iOS: placeholder shown), verify non-sensitive screens still allow (UX), check app switcher preview (blur or hidden). Phase 3 - Compliance validation (Week 4): (1) Static analysis: run SAST tools (MobSF, Checkmarx), scan for remaining vulnerabilities (insecure storage, crypto issues), fix findings. (2) Dynamic analysis: penetration testing (simulate attacks, MITM attempts with pinning fail, token extraction impossible), use Burp Suite,OWASP ZAP (proxy traffic, fuzz inputs). (3) Code review: security-focused review (all token access, network calls, crypto usage), checklist validation (OWASP Mobile Top 10). (4) Compliance audit: third-party PCI-DSS QSA assessment (Qualified Security Assessor), SOC 2 Type II audit (6-12 months continuous compliance), provide evidence (code snippets, architecture docs, test results). (5) Ongoing monitoring: integrate SAST into CI/CD (fail builds on security issues), dependency scanning (detect vulnerable libraries, Snyk/Dependabot), runtime monitoring (crash analytics for anomalies, fraud detection). Migration strategy for live users: (1) Phased rollout: release to 1% users (canary), monitor crash rates, errors, expand to 10%, 50%, 100% over 2 weeks. (2) Backward compatibility: app version N supports old (SharedPrefs) and new (Keychain), migration on first launch, users on old version auto-migrate on update. (3) Force update: after 90 days, require update (old versions blocked at API level), ensures all users on secure version. (4) Communication: in-app notification "Security upgrade required", App Store update notes "Enhanced security features". Testing matrix: (1) Devices: Android 9-14, iOS 13-17, rooted/jailbroken variants, low-end devices (performance). (2) Scenarios: fresh install (tokens stored encrypted), upgrade from insecure version (migration works), network (all calls HTTPS), screenshots (blocked on sensitive). (3) Automation: integration tests for security (attempt HTTP = fails, token storage = keychain, screenshot attempt on FlagSecure screen). Expected outcomes: Tokens: 100% in secure storage (Keychain/Keystore), encrypted at rest, biometric-protected. Network: 0 HTTP calls (all HTTPS, TLS 1.2+), certificate pinning on payment endpoints (optional but ideal). API keys: 0 hardcoded (fetch from backend or build config), obfuscated if client-side. Root/jailbreak detection: warn users, disable high-risk features, <1% false positives. Screenshots: disabled on 10 identified sensitive screens, app switcher previews hidden (iOS) or secured (Android). Compliance achieved: PCI-DSS Requirement 3 (protect stored data ✓), Requirement 4 (encrypt transmission ✓), SOC 2 CC6 (logical/physical access controls ✓), App store approval (security best practices met ✓). Timeline: Week 1-2 critical fixes deployed, Week 3 high-priority deployed, Week 4 compliance validation and audit, Month 2 full rollout and force-update old versions. Post-launch: quarterly penetration tests (ongoing validation), annual compliance re-certification (PCI-DSS, SOC 2), security training for developers (secure coding practices).',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),


    -- Topic 70: Mobile Performance (5 questions)
    (346, 'What causes app startup time to be slow? How do you optimize cold start performance?',
     'App startup types: (1) Cold start - app not in memory, process created from scratch, slowest (1-5 seconds). (2) Warm start - process alive but Activity/View destroyed, recreate UI, faster (0.5-1 second). (3) Hot start - activity in memory,brought to foreground, fastest (<0.1 second). Cold start phases: (1) Launch process - OS creates app process, loads executable. (2) Create Application - Application.onCreate (Android), didFinishLaunchingWithOptions (iOS), initialization code. (3) Create Activity/ViewController - layout inflation, view rendering. (4) First frame drawn - user sees content. Target:< 2 seconds total (cold start on mid-range device). Common causes of slow startup: (1) Heavy Application.onCreate - initializing SDKs synchronously (analytics, crash reporting, ads), database setup, network calls, blocking main thread. (2) Large dependency graphs - Dagger/Hilt dependency injection, complex object creation at startup. (3) Layout complexity - deep view hierarchies, many inflate operations, custom views with heavy onDraw. (4) Splash screen delays - artificial waits (Thread.sleep), animations before app ready. (5) Disk I/O - reading large files, SharedPreferences access, database queries on main thread. Optimization strategies: (1) Lazy initialization - defer non-critical SDKs: WorkManager.enqueue( InitializeSDKs worker) runs background, only critical init in onCreate (crash reporting for early crashes). (2) Background threading - move heavy operations off main thread: DispatchQueue.global().async { initializeDatabase() }; Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor().execute { setupModule() }. (3) Content providers for initialization - Jetpack App Startup library, removes Application.onCreate overrides, automatic initialization: class AnalyticsInitializer : Initializer<Analytics>, dependencies resolved, parallel initialization. (4) Optimize layouts - reduce view hierarchy depth (ConstraintLayout vs nested LinearLayout), use ViewStub for conditional views (inflated only when needed), avoid overdraw (Layout Inspector shows overdraw). (5) ProGuard/R8 optimization - dead code elimination, method inlining, class merging, reduces DEX loading time. (6) Benchmark startup - Macrobenchmark library (Android): @Test fun startup() = macrobenchmarkStartup(...), measures cold/warm/hot starts, integrate into CI (regression detection). iOS Instruments Time Profiler: record app launch, identify hot spots. (7) Trampoline splash - show native splash immediately (LaunchScreen storyboard iOS, Splash theme Android), perceived performance (instant visual feedback), load in background, transition to main UI when ready. (8) Modularization - reduce appmódule size, dynamic feature delivery (larger modules downloaded on-demand), smaller initial binary = faster load. Best practices: measure first (real devices, not emulator - misleading), prioritize main thread (all heavy work off main), test cold start explicitly (force stop app, clear RAM, measure), trace with platform tools (Systrace, Instruments), set performance budgets (startup <2s, enforce in CI). Monitoring: Firebase Performance: tracks app start automatically, p50/p95/p99 percentiles by device, OS version, regression alerts. Custom metrics: log timestamp at key points (Application.onCreate start/end), send to analytics, track over app versions.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (347, 'How do you detect and fix memory leaks in mobile apps?',
     'Memory leak: objects no longer needed but still referenced, can''t be garbage collected, memory usage grows over time, eventually OutOfMemoryError (Android) or app terminated (iOS memory pressure). Detection tools: Android - Memory Profiler (Android Studio): heap dumps, allocation tracking, shows retained size. LeakCanary library: automatically detects leaks in debug builds, notification with leak trace (object graph to GC root), install: debugImplementation "com.squareup.leakcanary:leakcanary-android:2.x". Detects Activity, Fragment, ViewModel, View leaks. Android lint: warns some leak patterns (Handler, AsyncTask). iOS - Instruments Leaks: detects leaked objects (memory allocated but no references). Instruments Allocations: track all allocations, filter by class, find growth. Debug Memory Graph: Xcode visual graph, shows strong reference cycles, purple icons = leaked. Common leak patterns: (1) Activity/Context leak (Android) - static reference to Activity: static MyHelper instance holds Activity context after Activity destroyed. Fix: use Application context for static, or WeakReference. (2) Inner class leak - non-static inner class holds outer reference: Handler/AsyncTask as inner class keeps Activity alive. Fix: static inner class + WeakReference to outer: static class MyHandler extends Handler { WeakReference<Activity> activityRef; ... }. (3) Listener leak - register listener in onCreate, forget unregister in onDestroy: eventBus.register(this) without unregister, this referenced forever. Fix: symmetric register/unregister (onCreate/onDestroy, onResume/onPause). (4) Timer/Thread leak - background thread/timer holds object reference, runs forever: new Thread(() -> { while(true) { activity.runOnUiThread(...) } }).start(), thread never stops. Fix: interrupt thread in onDestroy, use lifecycle-aware coroutines (lifecycleScope auto-cancels). (5) Retain cycle (iOS) - two objects strongly reference each other: Parent has strong child, Child has strong parent, neither deallocated. Fix: one reference weak or unowned: weak var parent: Parent?. Common in closures: { [weak self] in self?.doSomething() }. (6) Collection leak - adding objects to static collection, never removing: static List<Listener> listeners.add(this), this never removed. Fix: WeakHashMap, weak references, explicit removal. (7) Singleton leak - singleton holds Activity/View reference: MySingleton.setContext(activity), singleton lives forever, activity leaked. Fix: Application context only,or clear references. (8) Bitmap leak - large bitmaps kept in memory: imageView not released, bitmap in cache never evicted. Fix: recycle bitmaps (Android legacy), use BitmapFactory with options, LRU cache with size limits. Debugging process: (1) Reproduce leak - perform action repeatedly (open/close screen 10 times), observe memory graph (memory keeps growing). (2) Capture heap dump - Android: Memory Profiler > Dump Java Heap, analyze with MAT (Memory Analyzer Tool) or profiler. iOS: Instruments Allocations > Mark Generation, repeat action, filter growth. (3) Identify leaked objects - search for Activity, Fragment, ViewModel instances, if multiple instances exist (only one expected), leak confirmed. (4) Find GC root path - leak trace shows references preventing garbage collection: Activity → Handler → Message → MessageQueue, Handler keeps Activity alive. (5) Fix leak - break reference chain: make Handler static, use WeakReference, or cancel messages in onDestroy: handler.removeCallbacksAndMessages(null). (6) Verify fix - repeat test, memory returns to baseline (no growth), heap dump shows single instance (not multiple). Prevention: (1) Lifecycle-aware components - use ViewModel (survives config changes, not leaks), LiveData (auto-removes observers), lifecycleScope (auto-cancel coroutines). (2) Code review - look for static references, inner classes, missing unregister calls, flag in PR reviews. (3) Lint rules - custom lint checks detect patterns (Handler as inner class = warning). (4) Automated testing - integration test navigates repeatedly, asserts memory stable: repeat 20 times { openScreen(); closeScreen(); }; assert baseline memory ±10%. (5) LeakCanary in CI - run instrumentation tests with LeakCanary, fails if leak detected. Best practices: avoid static Activity/View references, use weak references for callbacks/listeners, symmetric lifecycle management (onCreate/onDestroy pairs), test memory on real scenarios (not just happy path), monitor production (track memory metrics, OutOfMemory crash rates). Tools summary: LeakCanary (Android, essential for debug builds), Xcode Memory Graph (iOS, visual cycles), Instruments (iOS, detailed allocation tracking), Android Memory Profiler (detailed heap analysis), MAT (deep analysis of heap dumps).',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (348, 'What is the difference between bitmap pooling and caching? How do you optimize image memory usage?',
     'Bitmap memory challenge: images consume large memory (1920x1080 ARGB8888 = 7.9MB uncompressed), loading many images exhausts memory, garbage collection frequent (jank), OutOfMemory errors. Bitmap pooling (reuse): reusing bitmap memory instead of allocating new. When bitmap no longer needed (scrolled off screen), instead of garbage collection (free memory), add to pool. When new image loaded, reuse bitmap from pool (same size), decode into existing bitmap, avoids allocation/GC overhead. Android implementation: BitmapFactory.Options.inBitmap: val options = BitmapFactory.Options(); options.inBitmap = getReusableBitmap(width, height); // from pool; BitmapFactory.decodeResource(res, resId, options), decodes into existing bitmap. Pool management: maintain Set<Bitmap> of reusable bitmaps, size-based pool (group by size), LRU eviction if pool exceeds limit. Libraries: Glide, Fresco have built-in pooling. Benefits: reduces GC pauses (fewer allocations), faster image decode (reuse allocation), lower memory churn. Caching: storing decoded bitmaps for reuse (same image displayed again). Levels: (1) Memory cache - LRU cache in RAM: val cache = LruCache<String, Bitmap>(maxSize), fast access (no decoding), limited size (memory constrained). (2) Disk cache - persisted to storage: DiskLruCache, slower than memory (file I/O), survives app restarts, larger capacity (hundreds of MB). Image loading flow with cache: check memory cache → if hit, return immediately; if miss, check disk cache → if hit, load and add to memory cache; if miss, download/decode → add to both caches. Eviction: LRU (least recently used) when size limit exceeded. Android: Glide/Picasso handle automatically. iOS: NSCache (memory cache, auto-eviction under pressure), SDWebImage, Kingfisher (memory + disk). Optimization strategies: (1) Downsample images - don''t load full resolution (4000x3000) for small view (200x200). Android: inSampleSize: calculateInSampleSize(options, reqWidth, reqHeight), reduces memory 1/4 if inSampleSize=2. iOS: ImageIO downsample during decode: CGImageSourceCreateThumbnailAtIndex with kCGImageSourceThumbnailMaxPixelSize. (2) Decode format - ARGB_8888 vs RGB_565: ARGB (4 bytes/pixel, full quality), RGB_565 (2 bytes/pixel, 50% memory, reduced color depth). Use RGB_565 for non-transparent images where quality less critical. WebP format: 25-35% smaller than JPEG/PNG, supported Android 4.0+, iOS 14+. (3) Resize images - scale down large images before displaying: Bitmap.createScaledBitmap(source, targetWidth, targetHeight, filter), or Glide/Picasso: .override(width, height). (4) Lazy loading - load images only when visible: RecyclerView/UICollectionView render visible cells only, cancel pending loads for off-screen items: imageView.tag = url; load url; if (imageView.tag != url) return (scrolled away, cancel). (5) Precaching - preload images before needed: precacheImage in iOS (didChangeDependencies), Glide preload in Android (RecyclerView prefetch distance), balance: too much precaching = wasted memory. (6) Clear caches - reset caches under memory pressure: iOS didReceiveMemoryWarning: imageCache.removeAllObjects(); Android onTrimMemory: Glide.get(context).clearMemory(). (7) Animation frame reduction - animated GIFs/WebP: reduce frame rate (30fps to 15fps), subsample frames (every other frame), or use video (more efficient than GIF). Comparison: Pooling (reuse memory allocations, reduces GC, implementation complex, Glide handles automatically); Caching (reuse decoded bitmaps, avoids redundant network/decode, LRU eviction, Glide/SDWebImage handle). Best practices: use image loading library (Glide/Coil Android, SDWebImage/Kingfisher iOS), don''t reinvent (pooling, caching, threading solved), specify image size (override target size, avoid loading full res), monitor memory (track bitmap allocations, memory profiler), test low-memory devices (old phones with 2GB RAM, ensure no crashes). Libraries comparison: Android - Glide (comprehensive, bitmap pooling, caching, transformations, GIF support), Coil (Kotlin-first, coroutines, modern, lighter), Picasso (simple, older, less features). iOS - SDWebImage (mature, caching, progressive JPEG, WebP), Kingfisher (Swift, modern, similar to SDWebImage), Nuke (high-performance, pipeline architecture). Metrics: memory usage (keep under threshold, e.g., 200MB for image-heavy app), cache hit rate (>80% ideal, fewer network requests), image decode time (p95 <50ms, don''t block main thread), scroll FPS (60fps maintained, images don''t cause jank). Conclusion: bitmap pooling reduces allocation overhead, caching avoids redundant loading/decoding, combination (pooling + memory cache + disk cache) optimal, use proven libraries, optimize image sizes, monitor memory continuously.',
     'technical', 'medium', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 5, true),
    
    (349, 'Explain Android App Bundles and how they reduce APK size.',
     'APK size problem: universal APK contains resources for all densities (mdpi, hdpi, xxhdpi), all languages, all ABIs (arm64, x86), users download everything (only need their device config), wasted bandwidth and storage. Android App Bundle solution: upload single .aab file to Google Play, contains all resources/code variations, Google Play generates optimized APKs per device config, users download only needed resources. Benefits: ~35% smaller downloads on average, app under 150MB (can use instant delivery), faster downloads. Bundle structure: base module (core app), dynamic feature modules (on-demand), resource tables (strings, drawables per config), asset packs (large resources). Split APKs: Google Play generates: base.apk (common code), arm64-v8a.apk (native libs for ARM64), xxhdpi.apk (graphics for high density), en.apk (English strings), user downloads base + arm64 + xxhdpi + en only (not all variants). Configuration splits: (1) ABI splits - armeabi-v7a, arm64-v8a, x86, x86_64, separate APKs per CPU architecture, most devices ARM (don''t needx86). (2) Density splits - ldpi, mdpi, hdpi, xhdpi, xxhdpi, xxxhdpi, download only device density. (3) Language splits - separate APK per language download only user''s locale. Code obfuscation/optimization: R8 automatically with bundles, removes unused code (tree shaking), shrinks resources (unused drawables deleted), optimizes DEX files. Dynamic feature modules: large features delivered on-demand, example: camera filters (not used by all), install on first use: SplitInstallManager.startInstall(request), reduces initial download. User navigates to filters → download + install → feature available. Asset packs: large resources (game levels, HD videos), install-time (with app), fast-follow (shortly after), on-demand (when needed). Example: game 100MB base, 500MB level assets, base installs immediately (playable), levels download background. Development: build: ./gradlew bundleRelease (generates .aab), upload to Play Console, Play Signs APKs (App Signing by Google Play required), generates and serves split APKs. Local testing: bundletool (CLI tool), generate APKs locally: bundletool build-apks --bundle=app.aab --output=app.apks, install to device: bundletool install-apks --apks=app.apks, simulates what user gets. Limitations: (1) Google Play only - can''t distribute AAB to other stores (Amazon, direct download), must generate APKs manually for other channels. (2) Requires App Signing by Google - Google holds signing key (some devs uncomfortable), lost key if leave Play Store. (3) Testing complexity - must test all split combinations (different densities, ABIs), automated via bundletool. Comparison to APK splits (old method): APK splits (build.gradle: splits { abi { enable true } }), manually create multiple APKs, upload all to Play Console, more manual effort. App Bundle: automated split generation, Play Console handles delivery, easier. Best practices: enable App Bundle for all new apps (default since 2021), use dynamic features for large optional functionality (keeps base small), monitor download size (Play Console shows size per device config), test with bundletool (verify split APKs correctly generated). Size optimization techniques: (1) Vector drawables - replace PNG with VectorDrawable where possible (XML vs bitmap, resolution-independent, tiny size). (2) WebP images - convert JPEG/PNG to WebP (25-35% smaller, transparency support), Android Studio: right-click image > Convert to WebP. (3) Remove unused resources - lint: "unused resources" warning, R8 shrinks automatically with bundles, manual: delete unused drawables. (4) Minimize dependencies - audit gradle dependencies: ./gradlew app:dependencies, remove unused libraries (check imports), huge bloat from transitive dependencies. (5) Native library trimming - include only needed ABIs in bundle: android { bundle { abi { enableSplit = true } } }, exclude x86 if not supporting (rare). (6) Compress assets - ZIP compress large files in assets/, decompress at runtime, trade-off: CPU time vs storage. Monitoring: Play Console Download Size report: shows APK size per device config (Galaxy S21: 35MB, Pixel 6: 32MB), track over versions (ensure not growing), set size targets (stay under 50MB for Play Instant eligibility). Expected savings: 1 Universal APK ( 60MB with all resources), App Bundle (25MB for avg device = 58% reduction), Dynamic features (base 15MB + optional 20MB on-demand = users without features save 20MB). Conclusion: App Bundles significantly reduce download size, split APKs tailored per device, dynamic features enable on-demand delivery, required for Play Store (no longer optional), use bundletool for local testing, optimize resources for maximum savings.',
     'technical', 'easy', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 3, true),
    
    (350, 'Your mobile e-commerce app is experiencing poor performance: product listing scrolls at 30fps (target 60fps), image loading causes UI freezes, search takes 3-5 seconds to return results, and the app consumes 400MB of memory (leaking over time). Users complain about battery drain and crashes on older devices. How would you systematically diagnose and optimize performance across rendering, memory, network, and battery? Discuss profiling tools, optimization techniques, and performance monitoring.',
     'Performance problem breakdown: 30fps scrolling = frame budget 33ms exceeded (target 16.67ms for 60fps), UI freezes = main thread blocking (image decode or search on UI thread), slow search = inefficient query or synchronous network call, 400MB memory with growth = leaks + inefficient caching, battery drain = background activity or inefficient network/CPU usage, crashes on low-end = memory pressure (OOM on 2GB RAM devices). Systematic diagnosis approach: Phase 1 - profiling and measurement: (1) Frame rate profiling - Android: GPU Rendering profiles (Settings > Developer Options > Profile GPU Rendering > On screen as bars), green line at 16ms, bars exceeding = dropped frames, identify which phase slow (input, animation, measure/layout, draw, sync, command issue). iOS: Instruments Core Animation, FPS gauge shows real-time frame rate, Time Profiler shows CPU hotspots. (2) CPU profiling - Android: CPU Profiler (Android Studio), record session while scrolling, flame graph shows method time distribution, identify bottlenecks (image decode 45%, JSON parsing 20%). iOS: Instruments Time Profiler, drill into call stacks, heaviest stack trace = optimization target. (3) Memory profiling - Android: Memory Profiler, heap dump analysis, allocation tracking (what''s being allocated), LeakCanary (auto-detect leaks). iOS: Instruments Allocations + Leaks, memory graph (find retain cycles). (4) Network profiling - Android: Network Profiler (see all requests, timings, payload sizes). iOS: Instruments Network, Charles Proxy (inspect request/response, compression, caching headers). (5) Battery profiling - Androids: Battery Historian (detailed battery usage), Energy Profiler (CPU, network, GPS usage). iOS: Instruments Energy Log, logs power usage by component. Phase 2 - Scrolling performance optimization (target 60fps): Root causes identified: (a) Image decode on main thread - BitmapFactory.decodeStream synchronous on UI thread, blocks 50-100ms per image. (b) Complex item layouts - deep view hierarchy (10+ levels), measure/layout slow, overdraw (drawing same pixels multiple times). (c) No view recycling - creating new views each scroll (not using RecyclerView.ViewHolder properly). Optimizations: (1) Off-thread image loading - use Glide/Coil: Glide.with(context).load(url).into(imageView), automatically downloads and decodes background thread, caches in memory + disk, placeholder while loading. iOS: SDWebImage or async loading: DispatchQueue.global().async { let image = UIImage(data: data); DispatchQueue.main.async { imageView.image = image } }. (2) Image downsampling - load images at display size (not full 4K resolution for 200x200 thumbnail): Glide.override(200, 200), reduces memory from 40MB to 1.5MB for 10 images, decoding faster (less pixels). (3) RecyclerView optimization - provide stable IDs: setHasStableIds(true) + getItemId, use DiffUtil for updates (calculates minimal changes, only updated items rebound), set itemAnimator = null if animations not needed (avoids relayout overhead). (4) View flattening - use ConstraintLayout to flatten hierarchy (replace nested Linear/Relative), reduce view count (merge TextViews using Spans instead of multiple views), onLayout/onMeasure show up less in profiler. (5) Precaching images - RecyclerView.setItemViewCacheSize(20) keeps scrolled views in cache, Glide prefetch: preload upcoming images during idle. (6) Remove overdraw - Debugcoverdraw (Developer Options), shows colored overlay (1x = blue, 4x = red), eliminate unnecessary backgrounds (set to null if covered), use clipChildren/clipToPadding = false. Expected result: 30fps → 58-60fps, smooth scrolling, no visible stutters. Phase 3 - Search performance optimization (target <1s response): Root causes: (a) Synchronous network call on main thread: val results = searchAPI.search(query) blocks until response, ANR risk if slow network. (b) Parsing large JSON response synchronously: JSONObjectlarseresponse) on main thread, 500-item array takes 500ms to parse. (c) No debouncing - search triggered every keystroke (user types "phone" = 5 requests), server overload, unnecessary traffic debouncee. Optimizations: (1) Async network calls - Retrofit with coroutines: suspend fun search(query: String): List<Product>, call from lifecycleScope: lifecycleScope.launch { val results = api.search(query); updateUI(results) }, non-blocking main thread. (2) Search debouncing - delay search until typing stops (300ms): var searchJob: Job? = null; onTextChanged { searchJob?.cancel(); searchJob = launch { delay(300); search(text) } }, reduces requests (5 keystrokes → 1 request after 300ms pause). (3) Background JSON parsing - parse off main thread: withContext(Dispatchers.Default) { val list = gson.fromJson(json, ...) }, Gson/Moshi parsing CPU-intensive for large responses. (4) Pagination - don''t return 10,000 results (parse + render expensive), paginate: 20 results per page, load more on scroll (RecyclerView OnScrollListener). (5) Local caching - cache recent searches: LRU cache query → results, instant for repeated searches, cache for 5 minutes (validation). (6) Server-side optimization - database indexing on search fields, ElasticSearch for full-text search (faster than PostgreSQL LIKE), query optimization (join reduction). Expected result: search response 3-5s → 0.5-1s, perceived instant with loading indicator + cached results. Phase 3 - Memory optimization (target <150MB steady-state): Root causes: (a) Memory leak in listeners - EventBus.register(this) in onCreate, never unregister, Activity retained after destroy. (b) Unbounded image cache - LruCache with no size limit or too large (500MB), images never evicted. (c) Bitmap no recycled - large bitmaps (product images 5MB each) kept in memory, 50 products = 250MB. Optimizations: (1) Fix memory leaks - LeakCanary identifies: Activity leaked via EventBus, fix: unregister in onDestroy: override fun onDestroy() { EventBus.unregister(this); super.onDestroy() }, repeat navigation test: memory stable (returns to baseline). (2) Limit cache size - LruCache size = 1/8 device RAM: val maxMemory = (Runtime.getRuntime().maxMemory() / 1024).toInt(); val cacheSize = maxMemory / 8; LruCache<String, Bitmap>(cacheSize), evicts least-used when exceeded. (3) Image optimization - downsample images (discussed above), use RGB_565 for non-transparent images (50% memory savings), clear cache on memory pressure: onTrimMemory(level) { if (level >= TRIM_MEMORY_MODERATE) imageCache.evictAll() }. (4) Lazy initialization - don''t create all fragments/views upfront, create when navigated to, ViewPager2.offscreenPageLimit = 1 (default, only adjacent pages in memory). (5) Release resources - clear large objects in onPause/onStop: videoPlayer.release(); database.close(), recreate in onResume if needed, prevents holding in background. Expected result: 400MB → 120-150MB, no growth over time (stable memory graph), zero OutOfMemory crashes. Phase 4 - Battery optimization: Root causes: (a) Frequent wake locks - app prevents device sleep (acquiring wake lock indefinitely). (b) Polling network requests - fetch updates every 10 seconds (even when app backgrounded), battery drain. (c) Location updates - GPS on continuously (high accuracy = power hungry). (d) Inefficient network - many small requests (100 API calls), each radio activation costs battery, vs batched requests. Optimizations: (1) WorkManager for background tasks - replace polling with WorkManager periodic work (minimum 15 minutes): PeriodicWorkRequestBuilder<SyncWorker>(15, TimeUnit.MINUTES), system batches work (multiple apps sync together = single radio activation), respects Doze mode. (2) Push notifications - replace polling with FCM/APNs push, server pushes updates (app passively receives), near-zero battery impact vs constant polling. (3) Location optimization - request coarse location if precise not needed: locationRequest.priority = PRIORITY_BALANCED_POWER_ACCURACY, reduce update frequency: interval = 5 minutes vs 10 seconds, stop location updates when app backgrounded. (4) Batch network requests - consolidate: 1 request fetching 10 product details vs 10 separate requests, reduces radio active time, compression (GZIP responses, smaller payloads). (5) Cache aggressively - HTTP cache headers honored (Cache-Control: max-age=3600), avoid redundant fetches, Offline-first architecture (show cached data immediately, refresh background). Expected result: battery usage reduces from top-3 drain to normal range, battery historian shows reduced awake time, network radio activations reduced 80%. Phase 5 - Testing on low-end devices: (1) Target devices - test on Android 4GB RAM, old chips (Snapdragon 600 series), iOS iPhone 8 (2GB RAM), slowest supported devices = performance floor. (2) Throttling - Chrome DevTools network throttle (simulate 3G), CPU throttle (simulate slow processor). (3) Stress testing - automated test: scroll list 100 times, open/close 50 products, search 20 queries, assert: FPS >50fps average, memory <200MB peak, zero crashes. (4) Monkey testing - adb shell monkey -p com.app --throttle 100 -s 500 10000 (random events), ensures no crashes under stress. Phase 6 - Performance monitoring in production: (1) Firebase Performance Monitoring - automatic tracking (app start time, screen rendering, network requests), custom traces (search latency, checkout flow), device/OS/app version breakdown, percentiles (p50, p95, p99), alerting on regressions (p95 search >2s = alert). (2) Crash reporting - Firebase Crashlytics (OOM crashes, ANRs), log memory usage before crash (identify pattern), device distribution (crashes concentrated on low-RAM devices). (3) Vitals monitoring (Google Play Console) - ANR rate (goal <0.5%), crash rate (goal <1%), excessive wakeups/wakelocks flagged, bad behavior warnings (impacts Play Store ranking). (4) Custom analytics - log performance events: event("image_load_time", time=120ms), track distribution (histogram), p95 optimization targets. (5) A/B testing performance changes - rollout optimization to 10% users, compare metrics vs control group (FPS, memory, battery, crash rate), expand if improved. Performance budgets and CI integration: (1) Set targets - app start <2s, list scroll 60fps, search <1s, memory <150MB, APK size <50MB. (2) Automated tests - Macrobenchmark (startup, scrolling FPS), assert budgets: assert(fps.median > 55), fail build if violated, prevents regressions. (3) Performance regression detection - track metrics per commit (grafana dashboard trending), alert on degradation (FPS drops 10%). Expected outcomes post-optimization: Scrolling: 30fps → 60fps (smooth, no dropped frames). Search: 3-5s → 0.8s (perceived instant with debounce + loading state). Memory: 400MB leaking → 130MB stable (no growth, zero OOMs). Battery: heavy drain → normal usage (10% → 3% per hour active use). Crashes: 5% crash rate → 0.2% (low-end devices stable). User satisfaction: ratings improve (slow performance complaints eliminated), engagement increases (users spend longer in app, less frustration). Timeline: Week 1 profiling and diagnosis (identify bottlenecks in all areas), Week 2-3 optimization implementation (parallel work: scrolling, search, memory, battery teams), Week 4 testing and validation (QA on range of devices, automated tests), Week 5 phased rollout (10% → 50% → 100%, monitor metrics), ongoing monitoring and iteration.',
     'technical', 'hard', 'organization', 1, 'custom', 7, true),

